reviewText: My husband and I would have enjoyed this action flick a lot more had they not felt the need to swear every 5 minutes.  A little swearing is not distracting, but when you have F--- being said more often than any other swear word, I have a problem.  Also, the bloodshed is a little too graphic.  In most shoot-em-up movies, people get shot and you see blood.  Here, you not only see them get shot, you also see their brain matter blow out the other side of their head.  That's just not necessary.All told, this would be a great movie to see edited for television.
summary: Good plot but a lot of swearing & graphic bloodshed

reviewText: I first watched this movie on Netflix and really enjoyed it. Arnold retires from the LA police force and takes on the job of a small town Marshal only to find out there is an escaped ruthless drug lord headed for his town.  Arnold and his crew of misfits plan to make a stand to hold off the menace while the feds try to get to him for help, that's the basic story. reviewText: Arnold is finally back in a starring vehicle for the first time since Terminator 3.  Sure, he popped up in the Expendables flicks, but those weren't headliners for him.  There was a lot of years of anticipation for the Arnold fan of whether or not this movie could possibly live up to those kind of expectations.I will say this, The Last Stand is not a bad movie.  Neither is it a particularly great movie.  I would say it's a middle of the road Arnold movie, but nothing like what we expected and usually got out of the man in his heyday.  To be fair, and it pains me to say this about the icon, but his heyday has passed.  So, in all honesty, this is the type of movie we should expect from him.We tend to forget that before Arnold went off to play politics in the state of California, other than Terminator 3, his movies were no longer banking like they used to.  I feel The Last Stand is certainly better than some of those movies he was making before T3; you know, your Collateral Damages, your End of Days or Jingle All the Ways.  Every single one of those movies I saw in the theater, and this one I didn't.  Go figure.A few things that I really dug about the movie.  It doesn't try to be a slam bang, over the top 100 million dollar budget blockbuster from Arnold's past.  It's a relatively medium budgeted movie with a simple plot with Arnold playing his age.  Sure, they try to throw in a few Arnold-esqe one liners, but it's so not that type of movie.  There's a couple of nice action scenes in the first hour or so, one in which Arnie has to save his deputies that's pretty cool, but most of the good stuff is saved for the last half hour, when we see the titular last stand.  There's a few tense moments, and the deputies get some good digs in at the bad guys.  I feel Arnold is very good in the last half hour of the movie, despite his age.  I thoroughly enjoyed Arnie and his deputies squaring off against the drug lord and his cronies at the end.Unfortunately, the first hour leading up to that feels a bit ho-hum and drags a bit.  I could of used a bit more last stand in The Last Stand.  This time of the movie is a lot of Forest Whitaker huffing and puffing and not really doing much of anything other than lending his name to the movie while Arnold doesn't have much to do other than act.  Let us be honest with ourselves, even as fans, this is not his greatest asset in the world of film.  Breaking bad guys' faces is.Still, it's a credit to director Kim Jee-Woon that even during the first hour of set up for the much better last half hour that he manages to move the proceedings along at a brisk enough pace that you don't catch yourself watching the clock.No way is this a bad movie at all, but it's certainly not iconic, like the Arnold greats of past.  And perhaps that's as it should be in this chapter of his life.As far as the blu-ray-ness of the flick, it looks and sounds great.  I had no problems with the presentation of the movie.  However, special features seriously lack.  I hate that, because I love me some special features.
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: I liked it and don't in the least regret renting this movie. This was Arnold without the Hollywood ego tripping crap like continually saying "I'll be back" or some other buzz phrase that ends up in 2 other movies. He appeared at ease and I liked how he interacted with the rest of the town's inhabitants. Most of the humorous parts were during those moments.The violence wasn't overstated with too much blood and they pretty much kept it separated from the humor. Pet peeve of mine is when ya get these stupid buddy/detective movies and they are cutting up like idiots right in the middle of a gun fight. I can suspend disbelief only so far.The rest of the cast fit in well and the plot was decent. Really the only thing missing was a cool dog, again my spin on that one.It flowed well enough that I didn't get bored. It's worth seeing.

reviewText: It seems everyone knows the drill in the internet age.. criminal goes free, western town, upright sheriff, good girl, bad boy, dumb deputy, free spirit in charge of arcane weapons(?) against the suave, the sophisticated, cruel, vindictive armani suit wearing criminall. Evil cannot stand against good. The law must hold. Ah, it's not too bad, but, if one pays attention and I did, it wasn't hard for me to see it all coming from way, way off, like a dust devil, no, dust storm on the flat horizon of the Arizona desert.Arnie's fun as the codger/sheriff who upholds morality, decency as he enjoys the peace of a small town after fighting crime in LA. But heck, Shane couldn't find peace in a small town either. Trouble just has a way..... That's about it for the story. If you enjoy westerns, Fast and Furious,Jackass, with small town corn thrown in- it'll fill the bill. Forest Whitaker does his best at acting. The rest try to measure up, but it's a mix of pone and car oil, with a chaser of speed and guns.

reviewText: A cartel boss ( Eduardo Noriega) manages a daring escape while being transferred to a jail and tries to head for the Mexican border in a fast car. The FBI ( Forest Whitaker) try to stop him but he manages to defy all opposition and heads for the sleepy town of Somerton and its Sheriff ( Arnold Schwarzenegger) setting up a stage for a final confrontation.The car scenes are just amazing and can be considered the highlight of the film.There are supporting players like Ray's deputies,  Mike (Luis Guzman r),  Jerry (Zach Gilford), and Sarah (Jaimie Alexander). Even other veterans like Forest Whitaker have not much to do. Johnny Knoxville is prominently billed but he does nothing but act like an extra.The main star is of course Arnold and I am glad he is back. He still holds a lot of charisma and a terrific screen presence. It is a pity that he did not choose a substantial movie to star in after a eight year hiatus, which is disappointing because the director Kim Jee Won has directed substantial Korean films "A Tale of Two Sisters,""The Good, the Bad, the Weird", and grisly cop "I Saw the Devil.

reviewText: This movie was terrible!!!  It couldn't decide what it wanted to be.  Was it a comedy or an action flick?  I guess it tried to be both, but it didn't work.  Let's put it this way.  Do you think slapstick comedy works when in the very next scene you have deadly serious hardcore violence?  Well, that's pretty much what this movie is.  I don't have a problem with some humor in action movies, but when it devolves into Barney, Goober and Gomer Pyle type comedy.......I lose interest.  That brings me to my next problem with the movie.  Every single law enforcement character is portrayed as a complete low grade moron.  I mean, calling them incompetent would be generous.  I suppose that's all Hollywood writers have these days.  Same old recycled characters rehashed over and over again.  It would appear that any low grade moron can also do well as a script writer for most of the movies out there today.I thought about discussing the plot, but why bother. The plot is so stupid and ridiculous, that I don't even feel like discussing it.

reviewText: I have long been a Schwarzenegger fan.  I love his flicks and the huge personalities he inserts into them.  They always have lots of self-deprecating humor to counterbalance the bullets and blood.  But this outing is not up to par.  Clearly, Arnold has lost a step, but he concedes too much of his superhuman prowess.  Who needs an Arnold as a mere mortal?  The story is more than predictable, and the action seems contrived.  Co-stars do the best they can, but the script is pretty bad; familiar and overdone in all the most important places.  I don't mind suspending reality... but this?

Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: This movie kept my interest straight through.  It was classic Arnold Schwarzenegger, despite him being older. The way he would stare people in the eye, classic one liners, muscle power, and that steely determination.  All hallmarks for Arnie.Even though the setting was a little no-where land town, it introduced the drama of this sleek, high-speed racing car with a mysterious Mexican cartel dude who was perfect for the roll of driving that amazing machine.  But equally matched by our Arnie, who opts for a sporty red thing that matched its power, and of course, he could drive just as well as the cartel guy.You asked for it, you got it.  Heart pounding action, funny lines and characters, and a story that moves right along.I haven't purchased a DVD in quite awhile, but after seeing this, I decided I needed to have it to add to my classic Schwarzenegger collection.

reviewerName: Chief Rocka Dr. Kool "Chief Rocka Dr. Kool"
reviewText: Unlike Stallone, Schwarzenegger makes a newer film at his current age while keeping it in tune with his age - not trying to be a 66 year old who still thinks that he is 30!This film was good ans too bad it did not do too much at the box office, but this turned out to be very good.  It is the usual ultra-bad guy action film, but it has it's twists and turns and Arnold acts his age and the movie flows with that instead of trying to relive his younger years.  Of course the usual double cross takes place here, but what do you expect?Forrest Whitaker does a great job as an FBI agent in charge.  I did not even know he was in this film until I saw it!  Maybe if they would have promoted it with him, it would have worked better.  Whitaker was very believable and natural flowing with his acting.  Arnold of course is always stiff and devoid of emotion, but that is not why he got a career in film to begin with.  The only other thing I don't like was he was a small country town sheriff with a heavy German accent, but no one in the film ever questioned why or asked where he was from, even though he said he was an immigrant later in the film, but that was politics.Overall I like this and this is a more sensible film to make for an old man former action hero and not an embarrassment like Stallone's films where he must still think he looks like he did in 1990.
summary: A lot Better Than I Thought

reviewText: After a stint as Governor of California, Arnold Schwarzenegger has returned in his first lead role as an actor. With his life full of scandal and his ability to win back an audience in question, Arnold certainly reminds me of why he was such a successful movie star in the first place. He may (I take that back). He will never win an Oscar in his life, although I think Schwarzenegger's future as an actor is well in tact for one simple reason. He is oozing with charisma.I was reminded of this after watching the charisma-challenged Colin Farrell step into his shoes in "Total Recall" earlier this year. Regardless of what you think of Arnold Schwarzenegger, he shines on screen when it comes to bringing you, the audience, into his films and making you care about him and the others around him. Apparently Hollywood thinks the same because including "The Last Stand" he has eight movies in the works through 2014."Last Stand" takes place in a small, nothing ever happens here, Arizona border town with probably too many police officers; four. Schwarzenegger plays Ray Owens, a former Los Angeles police officer who came to Arizona to get away from the relentless chaos and trials of big city police work. His fellow officers are just the opposite. They are either not prepared for such police work or eager for such police work. So when a ruthless Mexican drug kingpin escapes from FBI custody and begins hurtling their way in a specially outfitted car that is capable of going 200 MPH, they are about to get more trouble then they bargained for."Last Stand", along with Schwarzenegger, reminds me of how long it has been since a great action movie has been made. We've had action movies, but very few are worthy of repeat viewing or five-years from now we'll still be watching it. "The Last Stand" may just be one of those movies. The humor is plentiful and the personality is rich. The story is quality enough and the action never exceeds a level of reality or even comes close to a level of absurdity that we normally see in action movies these days. The movie is well filmed and has a level of coolness that puts it over the top.The only thing I would criticize about "The Last Stand" would be a fairly uncreative collision of bad guy and good guy in the middle of town. Where most of the movie was creative and had numerous moments that led the audience to believe that the officers of this tiny town were pretty much doomed. The cartel finally just show up in town, line up across the street (I think there were 9) and declare everybody dead. The movie, as creative as it was, could have done better.This one criticism is a pretty small detail in a movie that otherwise was a smashing success of entertainment, action and comedy. "The Last Stand" is a throwback to when action movies were good. There was a time when action movies didn't rely on absurd stunts that cross into fantasyland or had herky-jerky MTV editing that disguised how poorly the scenes are choreographed or assumed that the audience was only interested in 100-minutes of bullets zipping. Hopefully "The Last Stand" is a return to that notion.
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: I saw this movie a few days ago by renting it from Redbox's most famous Hit & Miss categories. I just made that up of course, there is not such category but there ought to be. I believe Redbox is hitting my dopamine receptors a little too precisely, like a gambling machine I can't stay away from really great to really bad movies, all of which have passed my retina in the name of self-enlightenment or entertainment.This was one of the worst movies I have ever seen, it's right up there with AI and Madonnna's Swept Away. Some great actors starred, like the truly divine Forrest Whitaker, and for what he's worth, that Austrian dude whose name I can't spell right now but who rocked in all the Terminator movies.This is not an action flick in the likes of Vin Diesel, Milla Jovovich or Jason Statham (can't think of any black action heroes right now, weird. That bothers me a lot. Which black actor is on par with Vin Diesel and Jason Statham? Will Smith? Maybe. But when we think of franchises like the ones Tom Cruise or Matt Damon star in, only Lawrence Fishburn comes to mind and gorgeous Jamie Foxx, who should have a franchise like Terminator, Iron Man or the Fast and the Furious.This is action driven, humorless drab, and it's unfortunate because plot is equally important as new tricks (I refer back to Jason Statham, who supersedes stunts with every movie he does, and keeps thinking of innovative ways to brutally beat up his opponents). An example of an amazing action flick with incredible stunts, dialogue, plot and humor was "Get the Gringo" with Mel Gibson. Thank you, Redbox, that was a hit.Get the GringoI only watched this because it was filmed here in NM and it doesn't hurt to see how our tax dollars keep Hollywood at work. Unfortunately from the get go it was one lame action sequence after the other, dimensionless acting, Forrest was greatly underutilized, and again, no humor. And what's up with all the head shots?! Yes, every single bullet fired caused exploding heads. A little overdone, don't you think, Special F/X department and Director?The only good thing about "The Last Stand" was a stack of Reason magazines on the couch, and with my cat sleeping in my lap I spend a wonderful afternoon. Lastly, I forgot to mention Dwayne Johnson. He may be the proper heir to Arnold, who should go back to politics and stay there. Evidence: "The Rundown".The RundownOf course, that also had Rosario Dawson, Christopher Walken and Sean William Scott. And humor.

reviewText: The Last Stand did not have the action, tone or pace that I thought it would.  The trailers made it out to be a sort of throwback to action films of the 80s.  What we get is a series of not-very-well-choreographed action sequences, much too much plot, shallowly written supporting characters with subplots that seem to go nowhere, and way too much time spent with the bad guys.  I guess the film was entertaining enough for what it was, but it never once hit the bullseye for me.  Arnold was in decent form, however.  I just wish he had a cooler script to return with.

reviewText: The story is wonderfully preposterous: a cartel drug lord escapes the clutches of an over-serious Forest Whitacker.  He then kidnaps a female agent and takes off south in a souped-up sports car that can outrun a helicopter.  Naturally, the entire Federal Bureau of Investigation doesn't stand a chance against him.  Who does?  One old sheriff in a small border town, teaming up with some local misfits (including, for some reason, Johnny Knoxville, as well as Luis Guzman wielding an impressive broadsword, which is kinda cool actually).There was so much promise in THE LAST STAND.  It had all the trappings of the old Schwarzenegger classics: stalwart hero whose honor is impeccable; a nice array of supporting characters who get a bit too much screen time, but it's okay because they're weird; a deliciously evil villain (Peter Stormare, who's actually the second-in-command, but that just means he gets more screen time than his boss); and a relatively short running time that kind of crawls along at first, but picks up in the third act.  And, of course, there's Arnold himself, as charismatic as ever.  He doesn't get quite as many one-liners (the film is way too serious for its own good; more on that in a moment), but he's surprisingly still game.  Politics may have slowed the big guy down a bit, but that just means he takes his time before opening up a can of whoop-butt.So why only three stars, you ask?  Because director Kim Jee-Woon has taken a simple American action film and tried to stylize it like an Asian action film.  Don't get me wrong; the new wave of Asian/European action films are fantastic, and certainly deserve their place in cinema.  But that style doesn't mesh well with a Schwarzenegger film.  And make no mistake: from the terrible script to the predictable twists and turns, this is a Schwarzenegger action vehicle (the same kind that also sometimes stars Stallone, Van Damme, and, once upon a time, Seagal).  We expect violence, but we expect it toned down; kids find their way into Arnold films after all (I devoured all of them before the age of 12).  We don't expect artful sprays of blood and dismemberment; bouncing body parts do not belong in this type of film.  As for the tone...the film is WAY too serious.  Again, that springs from it trying to be too much...or, rather, from Jee-Woon trying to make too much out of it.  THE LAST STAND wasn't meant to be artful; it was meant to be fun.  It still is, in spots, but alas...it's a welcome return for Schwarzenegger, who probably doesn't have many years of doing this left to him.  But he deserved a better comeback vehicle, or at least a less ambitious driver behind the wheel.
summary: A welcome return from Arnold, but the film tries to be too much.

reviewText: Years ago on a chat show Arnold Schwarzenegger was asked about his limitations as an actor.  His response was he couldn't play Hamlet but Olivier couldn't play the Terminator.  "The Last Stand" is testament that Arnold is back in a big way.  It's a film that harkens back to his heyday in that it's heavy on action but also story and character driven.  Arnold slips into his bordertown sherriff duds like he wore his Terminator leathers.  The stunt work, notably the car chases, are absolutely jawdropping.  This film is oldschool in a good way.  It puts the tired 3-D CGI exercizes to shame.  I know that Arnold has been tabloid fodder of late and it's fashionable to dismiss him as a hasbeen.  This film bombed out of theatres before I knew it even existed.  "The Last Stand" deserves to be a home video hit that it was denied at the multiplexes.
summary: Arnold In The Twilight Of His Years

reviewText: When I first saw the ads for "The Last Stand" I was naturally fearful that it would be every bit as bad as that first trailer made it appear. However I'm glad I didn't let that first trailer keep me from seeing the film. "The Last Stand" is a silly action filled romp with all the campy dialogue that made so many Arnold movies in the 80's so much more than simple action films. Above all else the film is fun to watch. Arnold gives us a more introspective character than I have ever seen him play before, but his performance as this aged and burnt out Sheriff is just as easy to root for as the more swashbuckling characters he played so often in his youth. He is joined by a strong supporting cast including two villains both of whom are just crying out for pain which Arnold is more than happy to supply.If you're an Arnold fan this one is a keeper and for everyone else give this movie a rent some night when you feel like an action movie.
summary: The Last Stand may not be the best Arnold movie, but it is every bit as good as everything else in his library

reviewText: {3.5 stars}Nothing too deep or complex, and could be called a bit predictable. Still, THE LAST STAND is well-filmed and well-acted and accomplishes what it sets out to do quite well. There are some decent twists and surprises here, as well as many good chase scenes. Schwarzenegger really shines as a very human hero, Sheriff Ray Owens of Sommerton Junction, AZ.I usually don't like films that try to combine ultra-violence and gore with slapstick humor, but THE LAST STAND does this in just the right places to just the right extent. While it's intended as a basically serious film, it also makes some brief but very natural transitions into a spaghetti western spoof. Enjoyed it!

reviewText: Arnold Schwarzenegger may be getting a little long in the tooth, but he's back in an action movie and it's not bad.  "The Last Stand" has a cartel boss (Edward Noriega) staging a spectularly good escape from federal custody in Las Vegas and high-tailing it for the Mexican border in a hot car with an FBI agent as hostage.  Schwarzenegger is the sheriff of the small Arizona town on the border where the cartel boss plans to cross into Mexico, with a few of his thugs clearing the way.  The premise is a nice setup for lots of car chases, gunfights, one-liners, and some redemptive behavior for the good guys in the small town.Sommerton Junction happens to be half-empty, with the mayor, the football team, and most of the citizen out of town for a big game.  Sheriff Ray Own, former LAPD police officer, is in charge and expecting a quiet weekend.  Not so much; first a gang of gun-toting mercenaries murder a farmer, then they shoot up a police car.  Owens soon learns what the FBI already knows, that the cartel boss is headed for Sommerton Junction, and help will not get there in time.  Owen rallies his deputes and the remaining townspeople for a last stand.The plot is pretty flimsy, but the action keeps the movie moving fast enough to make it all work.  Luis Guzman and Jaimie Alexander are good as Owen's plucky deputies, and Forest Whitaker almost steals the movie as a frustrated FBI agent.  There's a good car chase through a cornfield, and a great mano-a-mano confrontation on a bridge.  The movie doesn't take itself entirely seriously and neither should the viewer; recommended for Arnold fans.

reviewText: I know I can't be the first person to associate Kim Jee-Woon's amazingly tepid THE LAST STAND with late 80's / early 90's action cinema, can I?  This flick feels like it must've gathered dust for at least three decades without anyone so much as picking it up and offering a simple rewrite.  Why Arnold Schwarzenegger would choose this project as his `comeback from retirement' picture is a complete loss to me unless he wanted to remind his audience of what better he'd already done in COMMANDO, RAW DEAL, and ERASER.  What could make the argument that those films are equally forgettable, but, in the very least, that had enough spark to capture the limelight by being in the right time at the right place.  By comparison, THE LAST STAND feels like it may've birthed itself from some scripts rejected from TV's "The A Team" and "The Dukes of Hazzard."(NOTE: The following review will contain minor spoilers necessary solely for the discussion of plot and characters.  If you're the kind of reader who prefers a review entirely spoiler-free, then I'd encourage you to skip down to the last two paragraphs for my final assessment.  If, however, you're accepting of a few modest hints at `things to come,' then read on ...)Sheriff Ray Owens (played by legendary action star Arnold Schwarzenegger) is an aging lawman spending the last days of his career in the quiet li'l burg known as Sommerton Junction, a sleepy AZ border town.  However, the murder of a local resident kicks Owens and his three deputies into investigating what interest a Mexican cartel drug lord, Gabriel Cortez (Eduardo Noriega), may have with the city.  It turns out Cortez - escaped and on-the-run from the FBI - intends to cross back into his native country via Sommerton's lazy acres ... but he won't if the sheriff and his posse have anything to say about it!Now, to be fair, the description above actually details a story that I would've liked to have seen for THE LAST STAND; the problem is that so very much of the actual narrative feels constructed out of hackneyed drama and cookie-cutter characters that the film ends up almost entirely devoid of any impact.For his part, Schwarzenegger does the best he can with the material - a weak script watered down by background being "said" instead of either "explored" or "learned" naturally - but even he with all of his projected gravitas couldn't save this.  Instead, he's shackled with characters who probably couldn't pass an officer's exam even under duress - Luis Guzman as Deputy Mike `Figgy' Figueroa is only given comic relief lines; a usually reliable Jaimie Alexander is reduced to near damsel-in-distress status as Deputy Sarah Torrance; and (dear God) Johnny Knoxville as whacked-out-of-his-gord local resident Lewis Dinkum, a gun magnet with a penchant for naming inanimate objects.  Together, this team delivers one predictable line after another in a script that never quite develops beyond its hunt-and-shoot origins.What's even more frustrating is that the director - Kim Jee-Woon - has a fairly solid and significant track record in his native South Korea.  All too often, he gets pegged as a "visionary," but, for my tastes, I think he delivers films that look good but do occasionally feel a bit derivative; this isn't a bad thing, per se, it's just that I'd like to see him branch out a bit more creatively with some other influences.  His THE GOOD, THE BAD, THE WEIRD is a terrific homage to the spaghetti westerns of old, but it too isn't without a few narrative hiccups.  (Stylistically, it's accomplished and brilliant.)  His I SAW THE DEVIL is a solid slasher flick but ends up relying a bit too heavily on blood, gore, and shock value to be anything greater than a comparison to earlier (Korean) revenge works with stronger characters.  Perhaps his best film - for my tastes - is A BITTERSWEET LIFE, the bittersweet story of a gangster who does something upright and correct only to find himself now on the outs with the mob.  Granted, that film could also be compared to other Korean crime thrillers, but it still is one of the only pictures with Kim's name on it that I feel was truly `complete' so far as the characters, the story, and the themes are concerned.Perhaps THE LAST STAND will end up being little more than a speed bump in his (and Arnold's) careers.  I certainly hope so.  I think better things are yet to come from both of them ... but I'll never quite understand what attracted either of them to such a routine action romp as this.THE LAST STAND is produced by Di Bonaventura Pictures.  DVD distribution is being handled through Lionsgate.(MILDLY) RECOMMENDED.  I don't know what anyone was thinking when they put this one together.  THE LAST STAND feels like it's a script that sat in some exec's desk drawer for 30 years, and once Arnold Schwarzenegger's name got attached to it suddenly everyone wanted to be a part of it.  Unfortunately, the plot is borderline ridiculous, and the performances are pretty much a waste of celluloid.  Johnny Knoxville?  Someone actually thought that was a good idea?  Please.  Spare us your version of white trash, Tinseltown; we have plenty enough on our own.
summary: Neither Awful Nor Great, THE LAST STAND Feels More Like THE LAST STRAW

reviewText: After a disappointing turnout in theaters for Arnold Schwarzenegger's first leading role in a film since 2003, "The Last Stand" has hit Blu-ray and DVD. It's a good thing we live in a day and age where movies get a second chance in a home entertainment environment. All the people who dismissed it the first time can see what they missed out on.Ex-LAPD officer Ray Owens (Arnold Schwarzenegger) has retired to the small border town of Sommerton Junction. He's taken the position of sheriff in the quiet community. Things get heated up when Ray discovers the leader of a drug cartel, Gabriel Cortez (Eduardo Noriega), is heading through the heart of Sommerton Junction as he speeds toward Mexico and freedom. It's up to Owens and his inexperienced deputies to stop Cortez and his gang as they prepare for a daring escape across the border.Frankly, "The Last Stand" is the perfect vehicle for Schwarzenegger to make his comeback in. it's not an overhyped blockbuster or giant summer action film like a new "Terminator" would be. It's a more personal and low-profile affair which basically has the actor playing himself. He's getting older but doesn't want to give up on the adrenaline rush of actively working and doing something physically challenging. Schwarzenegger is the type of guy that knows it's almost time to start winding down but fights it tooth and nail.If you spent the bulk of the past decade mourning the loss of the 1980s and 1990s action films you grew up on, "The Last Stand" will fill that void in your heart. It's packed with that good old-fashioned violence, blood, and gore the politically correct will run from in herds. This is classic Schwarzenegger wrapped up in a new package.The high-definition transfer for "The Last Stand" presents a crystal clear picture and great 7.1 surround sound. However, the clarity doesn't distract from the gritty quality of the movie. Every blast of a gun, explosion, and crunching sound of someone getting hit blares out at the audience.A nice amount of special features are included in the Blu-ray release of "The Last Stand." There are three behind-the-scenes featurettes entitled "Not In My Town: Making 'The Last Stand', "Cornfield Chaos: Scene Breakdown," and "The Dinkum Firearm & Historic Weaponry Museum Tour." Deleted and extended scenes are also included. Johnny Knoxville and Jaimie Alexander provide first person "Actor-Cam Anarchy" as well."The Last Stand" may not be an innovative action flick that will change the way we look at the genre. it never made any promises to do so. What it does do is put Arnold Schwarzenegger back where he belongs. He's back in power as the king of action heroes. The aging actor might need to retire sometime, but it's not today!

reviewText: He's baaaaaaaaaaack!!!  Arnold Schwarzenegger returns with his first starring role film in 10 long years.  However, during that ten year span, Arnold did make several cameo appearances in various films, all while running the state of California as governor.  Since leaving office in 2011, he's had a rough couple of years in his personal life.  But, like many celebrities, he used the publicity to his advantage and now continues on with his career.  With his career in politics over, Arnold is jumping back on to the big screen, starting with the action-packed film, The Last Stand.In The Last Stand, Arnold stars as Sheriff Ray Owens, a small town sheriff trying to catch an escaped Mexican drug kingpin, Gabriel Cortez (Eduardo Noriega).  Owens, assisted by his deputies, Frank (Rodrigo Santoro), Jerry (Zach Gilford), and Sarah (Jaimie Alexander) - and their crazy gun-toting friend Lewis (Johnny Knoxville), this small town police force is on a mission to stop this dangerous kingpin from crossing back into Mexico.  Forest Whitaker and Genesis Rodriguez also star in supporting roles as FBI agents.Like so many of Arnold's films, there's very little that stands out about this film.  It is - by all definitions - a violent action film with very little substance or goals other than to shoot a lot of guns and blow things up.  Even though it's nothing new for Arnold, it's great to see him back in the saddle.  Granted, he's never been the perfect actor, but he's never really strives to be.  He has always brought a certain comedic charm, along with gun shells and explosives, that's still very enjoyable to watch.  Add in stuntman Johnny Knoxville as a sidekick for sporadic moments of cheesy, slapstick humor and it makes for a great deal of onscreen fun.There's not a whole lot to be dissected in this film.  It's just another recycled storyline that feels like a massive commercial for the incredibly powerful and stunning Corvette C6 ZR1 - which serves as a main character here in itself.  Regardless, if you're a fan of Arnold, then you'll be pleased with the result of this film and it will be right up your alley.  Once again, it's great to see him back on the big screen in a leading role and it almost makes you wonder how we made it without him for all these years.  Those brief cameos in The Expendables were well worth the teasing in anticipation of this day when Arnold would be back where he belongs - in this starring role, doing what he does best...kicking a$$.Overall Film Grade:  C+FNDNreview.com
summary: Arnold brings it in 'The Last Stand'

reviewText: Nice cinematography but that is the ONLY redeemable note in this lackluster waste of too much money.A one-dimensional Mexican cartel lord stereotype escapes from FBI custody and drives a real fast car toward Mexico.  Unaccountably, all there is to try to stop him is some police cruisers, a sightseeing helicopter and two vans allegedly containing a member or two of a SWAT team, who just can't do it.  And, of course, Ahnold.  The script is packed with unapologetic stupidity: the cartel lord turns off the headlights of the real fast car in the dark (he's driving with special nightvision!) and the helicopter flying overhead and spotlighting it loses the car and can't find it again; the real fast car causes the two swat vans to wreck and that's it, that's ALL the US gov't and the state of New Mexico have, now it's up to Ahnold; two real fast cars "battle" each and do 90MPH through a high corn field.With Ahnold, a thoroughly wasted Forrest Whitaker and supporting actors in throw away roles so meaningless that I couldn't muster any emotion other than small relief when the bad guys finally shot Ahnold's stock "puppy", the young deputy who looks up to him, had a promising future and wanted to go out and see the world, etc.  There is a "chick" with the good guys and a "chick" with the bad guys, basically interchangeable.Awful, just awful.
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: Just got this from Red Box for free, and man what a waste of time.  I love Ah-nold all the way but neither he nor ANY of the cast members took this South Korean-directed POS seriously. The opening sequence, with the state trooper, is just sooooooo bad, truly the worst of any this movie lover has seen.  Finally, why would this big cartel boss, who plans every little detail about his escape stateside, have not planned anything at all for his Mexican side?  Really terrible movie that should be rated -10 out of 10 stars.  Lionsgate should pay me for wasting my time!

Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: IMO, this was kind of a sad attempt for a movie. This movie is to great movies what a paint-by-number kit with five colors and the fifth one missing is to great art. Arnold looked tired, old and worn-out. His accent actually did him no favors in this movie. He seemed incredibly out-of-place. The movie itself was overly formulaic-- even the formula itself was overly formulaic. Most of the actors seemed to be barely going through the motions in that "I'm just doing this because the director has my balls in a sling" kind of way. I did find it interesting though how the people's heads splattered more when they were shot than the cart full of watermelons did which were shot with the same weapons. I'm trying to think of something positive to say about the movie, but I'm drawing a blank. All this is sad (to me) because I have always enjoyed Schwarzenegger movies, even when they have been over-the-top and campy. But this one didn't have any of that feel or flavor. It just came off as a weak attempt to re-ignite Arnold's movie career and just seemed kind of sad. I DON'T wish Arnold would hang it up though-- I just DO wish he would find a better movie vehicle with which to stage his come-back. This one just wasn't it. If you like watching people's heads splatter all over the place though when they get shot, this movie might be for you.
summary: Kind of a sad attempt for a movie

reviewText: Arnold Schwarzenneger's return to big screen action (if you don't count his cameos in The Expendables movies) really didn't create much of a stir when it was released last Winter.  I caught up with it on blu-ray the other night and it is an enjoyable little flick, certainly not top-tier Schwarzenneger.Arnold plays the police chief of a small town located near the Mexican border.  A former member of the L.A.P.D., he has survived a shootout that killed several of his friends.  He just wants a little peace and quiet.  This ends when a Mexican drug kingpin escapes (in a rather implausible manner) from the incompetents of the FBI who are bringing him to prison for execution.  He speeds towards Arnold's town in a souped-up Corvette at speeds of 200 MPH while his army of mercenaries builds a bridge for him to speed into Mexico.  The FBI, 2 vehicles of SWAT police and assorted other cops can't stop him..  It is up to Arnold and his very limited police department and the film builds towards its High Noon climax.Lets face it, the plot is of the made-for-tv variety.  It is on the big screen because of the return of Arnold, the greatest action star of the '80s and '90s, after his disappointing stint as Governor of California.Jackass star Johnny Knoxville was mistakenly listed as Arnold's co-star on posters when this film was released.  This is not correct, as his rather obnoxious role was a limited one.The picture and sound on the blu-ray were fine.  There are deleted and extended scenes.  There are some featurettes on the making of this film.  In them, Arnold's co-stars mostly talk about how thrilled they were to work with a living legend while Arnold himself slobbers on about how thrilled he is to work with the films brilliant and "visionary" Korean director.  (The director speaks no English and subtitles are used when he speaks.)Look this film is no Terminator, Total Recall, Commando or Predator.  It is a well-done and enjoyable action film and a welcome-return to the big screen for Arnold Schwarzenneger, a lot older and tireder looking than when we last saw him in Terminator 3.  But still able to hold his own in the brutal fight scene with the main villain that concludes this film..  If you like Arnold, you will enjoy this film.  If you don't like Arnold, you may still enjoy it anyway.
summary: Not Top-Tier Schwarzenneger, but Still Enjoyable Anyway.

reviewText: I did not have very high expectations as I began this movie, and I doubted that I would even finish it. However, since it was on Netflix, and I enjoyed Arnie's movies from the 80s and 90s, I decided to give it a try... and I'm glad I did. I was expecting something with very little effort, like the movies that he starred in just before his foray into politics (like Collateral Damage, for instance). What I got instead was an action movie that perfectly suits Arnie's current abilities (he no longer has Conan strength, though he's quite formidable for a person of any age, much less a senior citizen). The pacing, dialogue, and humor are all well done, though the movie drags a bit in the center, and you have to be willing to suspend your disbelief (as in all of Arnie's movies, if I'm not mistaken). The casting is perfect, and the story, though goofy and totally implausible, is actually quite entertaining. And the climax... it is an epic showdown that can stand beside any of Arnie's ending (except, perhaps, his legendary throwdown with the Predator). This movie is an unexpected delight, and a gift to all the longtime fans of Schwarzenegger. I can't wait to see what he does next!
summary: The Johnny Knoxville/Schwarzenegger Duo - Unexpectedly Awesome

reviewText: Some people have complained that this movie is weak on plot. I cannot agree. In fact, there is no plot at all. The entire movie is made up of car chases, shoot-em-ups, more car chases and then, for variety, more car chases. If you set the volume so you can understand the dialogue, such as it is, you will be deafened by the next explosion; if you set the volume to protect your hearing, you will miss half the dialogue. In fact, the best option of all is the STOP button followed by DELETE.

reviewText: Arnold is back and gives it his best in this new film on quite a different take from the Schwarzenegger we have all known as we became mesmerized to the big screen. Although Arnold is not as young and funny as in True Lies, not as series as in Total Recall, and not as strong as in the Terminator, the Sheriff he portrays in this Western is still entertaining. His job as a cop on the Arizona-Mexican border is to protect his territory, while preventing crime. Trouble brews as he meets a no-good Cartel boss with something real bad up his sleeves, and Arnold has to put it to a stop. Sheriff Ray Owens must gather his crew, not fit for the job, and stop the Cartel boss from building a portable bridge in Mexico. Arnold must defend his border, but his helpers may need a lot of backup. The bullets go flying, the story-line bursts with exciting action, and fighting gets heated up as it sets off the flames for the final showdown. Overall, this film is entertaining, and acting is good. Highly recommended for Arnold Schwarzenegger fans, and those who enjoy Westerns!

reviewText: The Last Stand is a movie that must be nominated for 2014's Oscar for Best Picture or at least shortlisted for that. The reason is that Arnold Schwarzenegger himself puts in a performance worthy to net him the Lifetime Achievement Award at the Oscars, the People's Choice Awards and even the Golden Globes. When you read my review of his mighty fine piece of thespian method acting, you, too, will understand why.The plot is simple, which alone should give this movie plaudits because it follows the "Keep It Simple, Stupid" formula. Schwarzenegger plays a retiring border sheriff by the name of Gerhard Knoblauch, and his deputy is none other than another equally highly regarded method actor, Johnny Knoxville. Together, they make up the law enforcement team in the tiny, American border city called Los Brokeback. They have to face a drug cartel boss called Felipe Calderon, who busts out of an American courthouse to hightail it back to his homeland of Mexico, that cesspool of murders, drugs and unbelievably unfettered corruption in all walks of society (are Club Med's down there still honoring coupons?)Of course, it's up to Knoblauch and Knoxville to stop that burrito from making it into illegal alien land, AKA, Mexico. The plot unfolds in such a seamlessly perfect way that explains why I'm calling for acting awards for Schwarzenegger. For example, every time Schwarzenegger opens his mouth to, I presume, deliver a line or two of dialogue, there is always this ungodly-sounding, thick, unintelligible Austrian accent that distorts everything and makes him speak in non-stop broken English. I mean, for an actor to be able to produce this fine piece of showmanship that has him looking like he's an Austrian refugee who's only pretending to be an American actor is breathtaking. Absolutely breathtaking.And don't even allow me to start on that brilliant supporting thespian named Johnny Knoxville; he is easily a cross between Lionel Barrymore and Jack Nicholson! Throughout The Last Stand, Knoxville's character comes up with increasingly intellectual ways to try and stop the Mexican burrito drug lord from making it back to Mexico. For instance, in one pivotal scene, Knoxville actually staples his balls/a/c/k to some cattle, which promptly stampede away, thereby elongating his body part. In another equally high-minded scene that is extremely relevant to the highly complicated plot development of this movie, Knoxville actually staples his butt cheeks together, then shoves a toy car into his a***, all the while dangling out of a helicopter and bungee jumping. All of these actions of brilliance work to actually stop the Mexican burrito from making it back to Mexico, thereby allowing Knoblauch to apprehend him and send him back to where he belongs (Barack Obama's White House, which makes him a citizen through the Dream Act!!).Folks, please, please, please do yourselves all a damn favor and see The Last Stand. I know, I know, I know that you probably have no money at all since Obama has failed to bring the unemployment rate down from January 2009, when he was inaugurated, but you at least caught a break through Obamacare, which raised your healthcare premiums! Yes. If you want to see the greatest movie made in the last 70 years, see The Last Stand.
summary: Arnold Schwarzenegger Has Finally Taken a Last Stand Against Everyone Else's Mediocre Acting!

reviewText: He said he'll be back, and whether you took it as a promise or a threat, here he is honoring that remark. After a decade of modest obscurity - Where in the world did he go? Was it some missionary work in India? - Arnold Schwarzenegger, 65 years old and perhaps reeking of Preparation H - roars back to action cinema. He's greyer now and his pecs don't quite have that old flex and form, but it's still Arnold, him what we action buffs loved back in the '80s. I guess absence does make the heart grow fonder. Let's face it, folks like the Rock and Vin Diesel just weren't holding it down. No one is quite as large as life as Schwarzenegger.Them powers-that-be, and this includes Arnold, are smart to acknowledge our guy's age. THE LAST STAND is generously peppered with snide remarks about how over-the-hill his character is. And since his age is addressed, we can ease back on bagging on how unconvincing this venture is. Arnold plays grumpy Sheriff Ray Owens, once a Los Angeles narcotics officer until he sought a more peaceful living in the sleepy border town of Sommerton Junction, Arizona. But Owens' "retirement" gig heats up when word reaches him that sadistic cartel boss Gabriel Cortez (Eduardo Noriega) has escaped federal custody and means to cross the border into Mexico. And Cortez may be heading his way. Owens' old instincts are triggered when he notices a suspicious crew of out-of-town truckers lazing about. His instincts don't play him false. These "truckers" are hard-core mercenaries set to rendezvous with Cortez. Man, if only there were a monster gatling gun in the house or something.And there is. One of the boons of this film is its entertaining supporting cast, one of which is Johnny Knoxville. He plays the local kook who runs the firearms museum and who gets some of the best lines and delivers onto the Sheriff a hellacious Vickers Gatling Gun. Knoxville, along with Luis Guzmán (irascible), Jaimie Alexander (cute and feisty), and Rodrigo Santoro (not cute at all and boozy), comprise Schwarzenegger's outgunned deputies. They tend to counterbalance Schwarzenegger's rustiness and creakiness. Give the Arnold a break. It's been a long minute since he'd starred in one of these.THE LAST STAND, treating us with a solid "R" rating, is Schwarzenegger at his most vintage. The film likens itself to past action hits that may have been less ambitious but were still massively entertaining (RAW DEAL, COMMANDO, READ HEAT, THE RUNNING MAN). There's a sense of campiness. The plot is wafer thin. Still, you're advised to be generous with the genre tropes and the inevitable plot holes. Despite that discouraging trailer, there's much to like onscreen. This is acclaimed Korean director Kim Jee-Woon's first English speaking film, except he doesn't allow that to hamper his style. He invigorates most every scene with vitality and a comic touch. He prevents the material from collapsing.There's a strong element of the Western, a whiff of oaters like EL DORADO and such. While the first half of THE LAST STAND is mostly set-up, the second half is an explosive, crowd-pleasing, action fiend's dream. Not that he has a choice, but I appreciate that Schwarzenegger sticks to what he does best: firing big guns, occasionally bestowing a wicked suplex on a fella, and dropping a deadpan one-liner or two. As always, Arnold indulges in a bit of self-aware humor. You don't see Arnold doing wire-fu. That would be a travesty. Schwarzenegger, looking fairly fit and spry (even his wrinkles have muscles), reportedly did as many stunts as he could. I guess the restful missionary work in India was good for recovery time from his exertions in past action thrillers.So it seems that he's back to stay, and I'm glad. I enjoyed myself silly watching THE LAST STAND. I don't know how much of my enjoyment was derived from nostalgia. Maybe later Schwarzenegger pictures of this ilk will end up boring the crap out of me. But not for a while. I'm looking forward to his upcoming projects: his team-up with Stallone in the prison break thriller, THE TOMB (2013), and most especially his reprise of Conan the Barbarian, THE LEGEND OF CONAN (2014). I'm a bit leery of TRIPLETS, his sequel to TWINS.
summary: ...triumphant return of the spell-check action hero...
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: Ok, so maybe Arnie isn't as young and limber as he was in movies like The Terminator films or Predator or The Running Man or Commando, but that doesn't mean he's not still capable of starring in a great action movie.  The Last Stand is his first lead starring role since his return from politics (with stints in Expendables 1 or 2 warming him back up for the big screen), and although it isn't the absolute best action movie out there, it still entertains!My dad and I both are long time Schwarzeneger fans...I grew up watching Schwarzeneger movies with him, and we saw many later films of his together too.  We both were jumping at the chance to see him on the big screen again where he belongs in the likes of Expendables 1 and 2, and once The Last Stand came around, we were sold on it as well.  My dad and I enjoyed every minute of it.Sure Arnie moves a little slower now that he's older, but he sure put on a good show in this film.  I won't go into too much detail about the movie, as you can certainly read about it for yourself, and I do believe a couple of other reviewers have already elaborated on the plot some, but I will say that my dad and I both enjoyed it.The action is good...with a couple of exceptions, there isn't a great deal of action right off the bat, but it gradually builds action-wise, until one big showdown at the end and a face off between evil (the villain) and justice (Arnie).  There was some good humor thrown in here and there too, and of course I had to chuckle at the fact that Johnny Knoxville was in this movie...before then I'd never actually pictured he and Arnie in a movie together, but it was honestly pretty great.  May not be an utterly amazing film, but it's entertaining and has some good action, and that's alright by me.  If you're an action fan, then definitely check this movie out!

reviewText: This tongue-in-cheek Arnie reboot is more entertaining than expected and relies more on some old fashioned Wild West Sheriff action than CGI overload. There's the improbable but spectacular jail break, some unlikely but gripping car racing against helicopters, and a reasonable young ensemble cast supporting the aging Governator in defending his tiny town against a ruthless but stereotyped Mexican drug lord.In case you're wondering, Arnie is looking old, and there are plenty of references to this throughout the film. Still, the action is well paced if not a little predictable and it's a fun way to spend a couple of hours with some optimistically inventive assaults by the bad guys, and the FBI operating in a less-than-competent mode while they wait for our small town Sheriff to do the jobs of an entire SWAT team.There are a few stunts that will have the ever-loving disbelief suspended away from you but the camerawork and direction is fluid enough to feel the excitement rather than unlikelihood of the whole thing. Personally, I was expecting so little out of this film given its dismal box office performance that I guiltily admit to quietly enjoying it. It's almost like the good old days of Arnold - if you bring some beer and pizza, you're guaranteed a mindlessly good time.
summary: Better than expected: Arnie out-feds the FBI in this silly but fun jailbreak caper

reviewText: This Arnold flick is a combination of several other movies, covering minimal ground, providing extremely predictable entertainment and action, very enthusiastic gun-play, and classic Arnold one-liners.Prisoner transfer under heavy surveillance goes horribly wrong – S.W.A.T.A vehicle being chased by multiple police units gets snatched up by a crane – Operation SwordfishBad guys have a secret way of crossing the border from the U.S. to Mexico – Fast & FuriousSmall town cop gets pressed into duty against superior bad-guy army – pick a movieSmall town cop deputizes Johnny Knoxville – Walking TallSmall town cop and motley crew hold off superior forces – Rio Bravo, etc.Throw in a cartel boss who also happens to be a professional race car driver, and the movie writes itself.  I didn’t hate it or love it, hence the 3-stars, but I was really hoping Arnold’s return would have more oomph.
summary: Lacks the classic Arnold punch, but probably worth a single viewing for action fans
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: "Governator Ah'-nold" is back. This R-rated action flick is targeted strictly for the fans of R-rated action flicks; I was surprised to discover that I am one of them! This fast-paced bullet-riddled comedy is entertaining from the first frame. I've never laughed through a bloody shoot-out before but our screening audience had a great time. Korean director Jee-woon Kim ("The Good, the Bad and the Weird") brings chop-socky experience and a great sense of humor to the screen with non-stop, cliché-ridden energy.All the humor is character driven, so let's talk about the characters:* Arnold Schwarzenegger ("The Expendables") is a weary sheriff in a little bitty (fictitious) Arizona border town, just putting in his time until retirement. He saw enough action in Los Angeles and was tired of blood, so he has moved here to relax.* Luis Guzman ("Journey 2: The Mysterious Island") is his chief deputy. He's not a coward, but he IS a realist, so when they hear that a high-powered jefe from a drug cartel is headed their way, he's thinking maybe they could look the other way "just for a little while..."* Zach Gilford ("Crazy Kind of Love") is one of our hero's hapless deputies. The first thing he does is break his nose while target shooting because he doesn't expect a high-caliber pistol to kick.* Jaimie Alexander ("Thor") is another deputy, scared spitless, but she's game.* Johnny Knoxville (Lots of TV) is one of the local yokels who volunteers to help our hero; but this gun lover INSISTS on being deputized. I laughed at his metal military helmet dangling on a rope as he is helped to cover.* Eduardo Noriega ("Blackthorn") is that aforementioned jefe, skillfully driving a singularly designed Corvette muscle car. He is smart, tough and determined.* Forest Whitaker ("Repo Men") is with the FBI; the stunningly clever jailbreak happens on his watch and he WILL bring back his prisoner, the most wanted drug kingpin in the Western hemisphere.* Genesis Rodriguez ("Casa de mi Padre") is a lovely FBI agent taken hostage by that nasty escapee.We have memorable thugs, a wonderful assortment of townspeople (some of whom have great reasons to stay in the diner), muscle cars, great use of a corn field, unlimited firepower, lots of blood, several humorous through lines that pop up at just the right moment, one little kiss and some appropriate profanity. I'm putting this one in my Guilty Pleasures file and look forward to Amazon telling me when I can get it on DVD.
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: It's pretty embarrassing, actually, this movie, and more so to admit that I actually enjoyed it.  Mind, I didn't enjoy it like I enjoy a good movie or a good "bad" movie, I enjoyed it because I was marveling at the fact that it wasn't made in 80s, but someone had a nerve to make this movie in the 21st century.  And as you know, in 80s, a lot of things just run on faith and faith only, so you just believe that, for instance, those people didn't need to go to bathroom, or Vette being driven at incredible speed would not need refueling, or the little Arnold is indeed an actor, that sort of things.  Yes, it's horrible, but embrace the horribleness, and it's kind of sort of enjoyable.  This probably doesn't apply to people who didn't grow up on the 80s movies...
summary: 80s throwback is not all that good

reviewText: I grew up a child of the late 80's and 90's watching and enjoying Arnolds movies so I looked forward to his return in the lead role for Last Stand. After watching the movie I have mixed feelings. Its good to see him again in the kind of role that made him famous, but it just isn't the same anymore. Much of that has to do with the movie being too campy at times with a convoluted and unbelievable storyline, but its also hard to watch one of your childhood action stars literally become too old to play a role like this convincingly, which is made worse by the mediocre story and directing. There are portions of the movie that are fun to watch and a few good jokes, but overall I felt unsatisfied at the end. There is a reason this movie was a bomb at the box office. Maybe some of that has to do with today's generation only really knowing Arnold as a politician, but its also because the movie just isn't that good. True Lies was a great Arnold movie that was able to be a serious movie and have great laughs at the same time. The Last Stand is a pale shadow of that. This movie is good to rent and watch for some decent action, but many true fans of Arnolds work will walk away sighing remembering the old days and better movies.

reviewText: I think there was a lot of wasted opportunity here.  There was a museum of weaponry which played a major role in the film, but that museum was reduced to just a single mention in a much larger conversation.  There was a shooting practice scene that didn't really serve much of any purpose, so I question why they did not expand on the story even more than that and show us the museum.  Johnny Knoxville needs more face time to bring to life his version of a crazed gun freak!The ending was also too soon. There was no answer to what happens next to the characters, so the end of the struggle never seemed to pay off.  I would have liked to see what happens to the bad guy and his only remaining associate.  I would have liked to know more about the sheriff's backstory.  Some more character development would have been nice.The entire film was fun to watch, though, and I love the cast.  For a movie that cost me nothing but time (thanks to Amazon Prime), I loved it.  If I had to see it in a theater or pay for it, I may have been a little disappointed with the lack of fun quotes and the rather straight-forward plot.  3/5 seems like a fair score.
summary: I can sum this movie up in 2 words: missed opportunities.

reviewText: I'll admit that I bought the movie out of a sense of nostalgia.  I wanted to see Arnold's return after his foray into politics, and I'm happy to say I wasn't disappointed.Of course the picture required some suspension of disbelief.  That's a given in the genre.  The good guys never miss and the bad guys never hit, for instance.  By the way, I lived in the desert for many years, and there were many cornfields within a few miles of my home.  All it takes is irrigation water, and I'm sure they have some in Arizona.The new, old Arnold was fun.  I'll be looking forward to his next one.

reviewText: I liked this movie, lots of action in this film. What you will notice after watching it is that most of the action is not right away which if you ask me gives a movie time to create a story, plot, you know something worth spending your time on. This type of movie in modern days is rare to say the lease, it is worthy of the 4stars. In this movie Arnold plays the role of an old time cop that lives in a small town, this day is his day off and hes not doing anything what could go wrong right? Well expect it all to happen, from hot bullets flying to fast cars crashing and a few hard throws with fist, lets not forget the unique guns used in some parts as well, this is a movie that will get your mind going right away, it will keep you guessing. Enjoy this speed ride from handcuffs to gun fights, it all happens.Please note that when i rate a movie i don't always give a movie 5 stars if i like it a lot, when i rate something like a movie i take into consideration that i have to look at it as if i was not a fan of the movie, say like i were just watching a random movie and type. So if i were to watch a movie i really loved and was a fan of it i wouldn't give it any extra stars just because i liked it more then other people did, and i think this is very important in rating movies.4 out of 5 stars, reasons are that it was a great movie however the action in it seemed a bit chill for the general parts or major parts of the movie, while this is not always a bad thing, in this case i felt that this caused the film to become a slightly lower standard in its area of action movies.Last note, I would recommend this movie to everyone, as long as they were over the age of 13 and understood fiction and truth. Also yes this was a great movie so by all means watch it lol. Hope this helped you decide on what to watch.

reviewText: This movie was better than I expected, but still much worse than I desire. Schwarzenegger has certainly lost his "charm" over the years. With actors who can actually act, his machismo schtick is no longer funny.This movie isn't intolerable. It has surprisingly good production value (e.g. there are some decent fight scenes with surprising effects and gore). However, it's story and acting are lacking. Save Last Stand as a last resort for a boring weekend.
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: Here I am with a review on this account. I have mostly done reviews for old Wrestling Pay Per Views & done my 20 years ago & 2003 in film reviews on my newer account. But anyway getting to this review for The Last Stand which is Arnold Schwarzenegger's 1st leading role in 10 years. Made on a budget of $30 or $45 million made a very disappointing $6 million in it's opening weekend the number 1 film of that weekend was some movie called Mama which I am sure is a run of the mill horror film. Or a movie like Machete that was suppose to be a exploitation, revenge film instead was about the border & very pretentious. This movie is what Machete should've been. Directed by Kim Ji Woon this has been the only movie that I have seen that he has directed. It stars Arnold Schwarzenegger as Sheriff Ray Owens,Eduardo Noriega as Cortez,n Johnny Knoxville as Lewis Dirkum, Peter Stormare as Burell, Jamie Alexander as Deputy Torrance Zach Gilford as Deputy Bailey, Forest Wittaker as Agent John Banister, Genesis Rodriguez as Agent Ellen Richards, Luis Guzman as Deputy Mike Figerola & Rodrigo Santoro as Frank Martienez. The story is you have this Drug Lord named Cortez escape FBI custody when his henchies takes this giant magnet that picks up the van he is in Cortez kills the guards he escapes takes an agent named Ellen Richards hostage & leaves in a Corvette C6 ZR1 that has been modified. Meanwhile you have this Sheriff named Ray Owens who is Sheriff in a small town he gets a call that this local farmer played by Harry Dean Stanton hasn't delivered any milk at the local Diner. A couple of his deputies Jerry Bailey & Sarah Torrance check out the farmers house where they find him dead they look outside where they find blood & tire tracks leading to The Canyons. Meanwhile Agent John Banister has the local cops set up a blockade to stop Cortez but his henchies gun the cops down a Bulldozer comes through knocks some cop cars out of the way Cortez speeds through in his Corvette & dodges the remaining SWAT Trucks. Then you go back to that farm house where Sheriff Owens & another Deputy Mike Figuerola they find the body & they find out that Deputies Torrance & Bailey are going into a trap. Then you have Burell a guy that is going to help Cortez escape The US. They open fire at Deputies Bailey & Torrance. Burell shoots Deputy Bailey in the back with a Sniper Rifle. Sheriff Owens drives up saves his Deputies guns some of Burell's hencies down with his Shot Gun. Deputy Bailey dies later on. Agent Banister contacts Sheriff Owens he tells him about Cortez. He prepares to go to war with Burell & stop Cortez. Owens Deputizes a local man named Frank Martinez cause he was friends with Deputy Bailey. Owens goes to this guy named Lewis Dirkum who has a lot of illegal firearms. He goes to The Diner & tells the people in there to go home for their safety. This scene is funny where the old guy tells him "I'm 72 years old I'm eating an omlet with extra bacon & cheese do you think I'm afraid of death." I know I messed that line up but. Then Burell & his men show up at town square where you get a series of really good action scenes where Deputy Figuerola is pinned down behind a car. This was really over the top in a good way where Burell takes a rocket launcher fires it at the car that Deputy Figuerola is hiding behind & Figuerola is still alive & comes out firing a machine gun starts firing it at Burell's men but he is shot by a sniper. You have Sheriff Owens in the back of an old School Bus firing a mini gun from T2. Dirkum shoots a flare gun at 1 of the henchies & he is blown apart. That character Frank comes into the picture he drives the bus into town square & runs over 1 of Burell's men. He also saves Deputy Torrance from being killed. The scene with the old lady is beyond hilarious. Burell tries to escape in the school bus but is killed by Sheriff Owens. Burell's phone rings & Owens answer's it. It's Cortez Owens lets him know who he is. Cortez speeds through town square Owens steals The Mayor's Corvette which you have a battle of The Corvettes. Not going further into the plot I pretty much told a little bit of what happens. The Last Stand was a fun movie & a solid 1 at that the only problems was it is kind of slow early on the main villain isn't all that great. But you have likeable & funny characters & some really good action set pieces. Kim Ji woon did a good job directing.  Arnold Schwarzenegger was really good. Forest Wittaker did a decent job. Johnny Knoxville was ok. Genesis Rodriguez was ok. Rodrigo Santoro was ok. Zach Gilford was ok Peter Stormaro was good. Jamie Alexander did a good job. Luis Guzman did a pretty good job. Like I said only 2 or 3 issues with the movie but overall a solid fun movie.
summary: Arnold still has it 8/10 might have spoilers
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: The brutality and the unimaginable wealth of the Mexican Drug Cartels is over-played in this film for the returning "Ahhnold"...It is perhaps one of the better 'returns' that could have been planned for Schwarzenegger. Playing a remote border Sheriff in Texas who just wanted to be left alone. Then, perhaps because of the remote location, the Mexican Drug Cartel's escaping leader decides to invade the self-induced exile to the nether-regions of the Texas borders.The story is believable to most of America that has not experienced the NEW border crossings of USA-MEXICO. The Sheriff is bigger than life itself, enduring unending tortuous pain to rise up victorious.Good acting (sometimes stretched) combined with unbelievable gun battles where the strength of the Texas Cars are shown to be better than anything Detroit built, delivers all the action that you will need.  Do I recommend it? Yes, if for nothing else, the fantasy action-drama that it provides; an escape from the troubles of our own times.  Add it to your collection!
summary: The Last Stand, for the Sheriff, for the Cartel Leader
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: Note: May contain spoilers. Proceed with caution.Now that's what I'm talking about! It's been quite some time since we've seen Schwarzenegger in a lead role, but he comes back hard with his latest action flick, The Last Stand. I can't say that I've ever been a Schwarzenegger enthusiast by any means, but I understand his significance in the film industry so I've never been able to write him off completely. To be honest, I only watched The Last Stand out of sheer curiosity, but damn did I have fun. Achieving the perfect balance of action and comedy, The Last Stand manages to not only be enjoyable, but it kept me engaged the entire time.You follow Sheriff Ray Owens (Schwarzenegger), a former officer for the LAPD. After performing a job that went terribly wrong, Owens resigned from the department only to settle in Sommerton Junction, Arizona. A small little town that sees very little action, most crimes in the town are petty and forgettable, but that's about to change very soon. Owens receives word that international drug lord Gabriel Cortez (Eduardo Noriega) has escaped from the clutches of the FBI in Las Vegas and is headed toward Sommerton. After meeting some suspicious truckers and finding the local farmer dead, he has a gut feeling that everything is connected. So he groups up his band of misfits -- Deputy Sarah Torrence (Jaimie Alexander), Deputy Mike Figuerola (Luis Guzman), former Marine Frank Martinez (Rodrigo Santoro), and local whack-job Lewis Dinkum (Johnny Knoxville) -- to stop Cortez and his gang and bring him to justice.Some may argue that the story is merely there as an outline for the action, but I think that does a disservice to the writers and the performers. Yes, there's explosions, firefights, and the like, but there's more to the story than that. To me, it was more about a man finding peace within his past. Letting go of what was and enjoying what is. From the get-go you can tell that Owens is a troubled character, but until about half-way through you don't know why. Then once you hear his story you understand and it all makes sense. Not only that, but you begin to feel for him because you can see the pain he feels both emotionally and physically as the story plays out. It was really quite surprising how real everything felt.Still, if blood and guts aren't your thing then it would be best to avoid this. While The Last Stand may not be an over-the-top gore-fest, they weren't afraid to let their imagination's fly in the final action sequences. It should be noted that most of this is done for comedic effect and I was actually surprised at how much I laughed while watching this. There was a point within the final half-hour where I began to cry because I was laughing so hard. Even when I called out a sequence beforehand it was still hysterical because I was still laughing from something that happened a few seconds prior. I always enjoy a good story that doesn't take itself too seriously and The Last Stand definitely falls into that category.As I said, it's been awhile since we've seen Arnold take the lead, but it seemed like this role was made for him. Maybe it's his years of experience or just his ability to get into character, but I can't picture anyone else playing the troubled Sheriff Owens. He gives off this very confident vibe the entire time which helps make the role feel comfortable and less stiff. It's this comfortability that becomes the driving force for the whole movie, in my opinion. Whether it's Arnold's performance as Owens or Forest Whitaker's performance as Agent John Bannister, the viewer can be at ease because no actor feels out of place. Even the minor roles like Sarah and Lewis felt perfect and it's almost insane how spot-on the casting was across the board. It's obvious that Knoxville was there more for comedic effect, but I find it hard to complain when the role was so perfect.Finally, the film's score, composed by Korean composer Mowg, was excellent. While there wasn't a lot of compositions scattered throughout the scenes, the ones that were there felt right at home. Most of them had this very Western-y kind of vibe which suited the film perfectly. I personally enjoyed these pieces more than the some of the high-energy compositions found during the chase scenes and such, but that's mostly because they seemed a bit more creative in comparison.Overall Score: 8/10 - I don't say this too often, but what I really enjoyed about The Last Stand was that it was fun. Pure, simple fun that wasn't brought down by a nonsensical story. It has heart and drive, but it was also able to give you some nice firefights and a handful of laugh-out-loud moments. The end result is definitely better than I anticipated going in. If you had your eye on this I would recommend giving it a shot. It may not be groundbreaking, but, like I said, it's fun and it has a really solid cast.
