reviewText: Man, Arnold Schwarzenegger is getting old! And believe it or not it shows! A lot.  I don't know why I liked this movie so much, I really don't. This movie warrants a 2 and a half star rating yet I switched it to 3 and a half star review. I just liked this movie for no reason. It kept my attention span. Arnold, who is now I believe 60, and when he filmed this at 58, seems to be taking serious damage at every step he takes. Sadly, it might be time for this old man to hang in the towel soon. This film isn't that great, this movie isn't even good, it's bad, and really lame, and laughable but for some reason I liked it. Not because of Arnold, Arnold, hangs on to this film like a dirty towel basically. Well anyways let's get on with this review, let's start with the negatives. The negatives include the cast, plot, Arnold Schwarzenegger, action, music, character development, the acting, and screen time. O.K didn't I tell you that there's a lot to hate? Yes, I know this is going to cause a small controversy from my fans. Well anyways most of this cast are just very poorly chosen.  While I love Arnold, I really think he should have been recast with someone like maybe Bruce Willis. Yes, I know I critically bombed Bruce, for Looper, but he wasn't right for that rule, I think he would have been perfect for this one though. And then we have Ms. Genesis Rodriguez, who was poorly cast, as well as comedian, Luis Guzman. For starters Luis just doesn't look serious enough to be a deputy. Well I can kinda see it but he doesn't seem right. And as for Genesis, how convincing can she seems as a cop? Not too much.  This movie's plot is very weak, and a bit loose. This movie falls threw a couple plot holes. Such as having too villains and neither really having any reason to do anything. I mean the plot is a group of people must defend their small town from a lot of invading bad guys. Wow, plots now a days are getting really thin. How far this go / a guy can tries to get to Mexico and with the help of a dozen dudes with guns and his 100 mile per hour car a lover hostage he can do it! This is nothing we haven't seen another hundred times before. Arnold, Arnold, Arnold.  Dude I think I have said enough about you, so let's move on. The action is very minimal, for a film that has little else to do then for explosions and action. The plot has nothing to do, it's so bored. I think they should have added more action, for the actors to do. Everybody just looks lazy in this film. The action is poor even when it happens, it's not well done and the action is 5 minutes in between each other. The music in this movie is very minimal, and not very well chosen. The music adds little to the action, and makes everything happening less exciting in my opinion. Man, why couldn't they pick up some of the soundtrack to Fast Five, and Rango and mash it up and turn it into "The Last Stand Soundtrack". Now that would be music to remember. But here we have a bunch of UN admirable music to add. Man one of the worst things with this movie is its character development. I mean i really just don't get any of the characters. I mean we have Johnny Knoxville as Lewis, and I really don't get who he is. All I know is that he has a museum and has a relic gun which he has named. I mean what? And also we have Frank Martinez, the villain who I really don't understand at all. Why, the heck is he in prison to begin with?  I don't really get it.  This film gives little screen time to the people involved including Johnny Knoxville's Lewis who we see only  for about 20 minutes altogether, which gives us no time to  develop his character as I have already talked about. Also they should have shortened, Peter Stormare's character, to add more time for the main villain to develop some more.  And shorten Forest Whitaker's character so that we can have more time for Sheriff Ray Owens, played by Arnold, to develop. Now onto the positives with this film including,  Rodrigo Santoro, ending, visuals, car stunts,  and just that I liked it. Rodrigo, was excellent as this film's villain, even though he was given a very small time on camera he was excellent in all of it. He really can act like a villain. He scared the heck out of me, he did. He was very devilish.  The ending was an epic car race between Arnold and Rodrigo's character; I felt that Rodrigo really had a chance of getting away until Arnold's Sheriff showed up at the bridge. The race and battle at the bridge were really suspenseful. I thought Arnold was going to kill him and the same for Rodrigo.  The visuals were spot on as well. Even though there wasn't much visuals needed, when the car crashed into the polish vehicles it looked really good!!! The car stunts were epic, when Rodrigo's character crashed into the police car and flipped it over that was really cool.  Believe it or not I just liked this movie. I know it doesn't justify why I would rate this 3 and a half stars, what with all the negatives with this movie. I just liked it and that's that.  Everything I said is kinda miner for me. All in All, this is a pretty big disappointment, but I liked it anyways. Arnold is getting way to old and it dragged this movie down a lot maybe he should go back to politics or better yet - retire. D+
summary: Arnold's getting old and it shows

reviewText: You don't start watching this movie because you think it's going to be a tear-jerking drama. It's got a very simple plotline. Super crazy, bad guy's headed for Sheriff Ray's small Arizona town in a souped up car, and only the Somerton's sheriff and a handful of motley deputies stand in the way.Things blow up. People die. It wasn't going for an oscar for best actor, but it fulfilled the purpose of offering a modern interpretation of the wild west revisited. Would have also worked with zombies. 4 stars for effort, action, the flare gun, and "Put the hurt on 'em, Ray!"Conclusion: Worth watching once or twice. Has subtle, dry humor sprinkled throughout. It might not be enough to keep everybody interested, but I enjoyed the mindless action it contained.
summary: Entertaining Mindless Violence, Fast Car Sort of Flick

It is not the best action film out there and the action at times is a bit over the top but the action does pick up in the second half and at least keeps you occupied for the duration. reviewText: I guess I am a simple person when it comes to movies. Real life (at least mine) is very complicated and can be stressful, so when I sit down to watch a movie, I don't want flashbacks or reminders of what I deal with in life. I am an escape artist!That said, there is a lot to recommend about this movie. Arnold Schwarzenegger for one. I am old enough to remember Arnold when he was a real movie star in the Terminator series, Total Recall, True Lies, The 6th Day, etc. One thing you could always count on when Arnold was at his best, was his sense of humor which was in complete juxtaposition with his appearance. He rarely took himself seriously even if the material he was acting did. That is a gift few actors have. And to see this Arnold up on the screen again was a joy for me to behold!I normally would not give such a fairly innocuous movie 5 stars. But Arnold once again, took the material given and made it his own. Which meant it was a rollicking good time with laughs and excitement and a bit of horror all thrown together. Simple ME! I loved every minute of it and, if you just want a fun, escapist movie to lose yourself in for 90 or so minutes, then this won't disappoint! His age is definitely showing, but instead of feeling melancholy about it, since the movie fit him so well, I was just in the moment with it. Besides, nothing lasts forever. Sometimes, though, we get a moment to relive a wonderful thing, and for me, this movie was that moment!

reviewText: If you're one of those people who think that the action film has sunk like the Titanic, gone the way of the dodo bird and disappeared like the Edsel (older folks will understand that reference), don't give up hope.  Arnold Schwarzenegger makes his return to the screen in what can only be called a fun-filled, action romp where you know the good guys are going to win and the bad guys will get what they have coming to them.  The fun is in watching it get done.  This one harkens back to when Chuck Norris, Arnold, Sylvester Stallone and others took a great deal of delight in dispatching the bad guys with tongue firmly planted in cheek, all the while making it look serious."The Last Stand" isn't one of those movies that's going to make you think a lot and it's going to make you sad to see some beautiful cars get destroyed, but for 107 minutes it certainly keeps you entertained and isn't that what a movie is supposed to do?  Lots of blood, guts, body parts, bullets flying everywhere and not a single moment of gratuitous sex tossed in - yep, not a single second of nudity or semi-nudity but with a movie like this, who needs it?It's a return to yesterday's action flicks and let's hope Arnold decides to make some more.  He certainly doesn't look like someone in their late 60's and is surely good for at least one more romp through action-movieland.  Get it, enjoy it, you'll be glad you did!!
summary: Just a Fun-Filled, Old-Fashioned Action Romp

reviewText: Ahnold has always entertained me, from seeing him in Pumping Iron as a kid and then Conan, the Terminators, Total Recall, a few other fairly fine films, and then of course perhaps his dramatic apogee as Mr. Freeze, a role that clearly would have received the Oscar nod if it was anyone other than Ahnold. But then Hollywood's anti-Austrian sentiment has never been a big secret.Sadly, Arnie's performance here is not quite up the lofty standards of Mr. Freeze, or even Lou Ferrigno (or Lou's dad). This may in fact be the worst on-screen work Arnie has ever done, which in its own way is quite a statement. But from the ham-handed and beyond ridiculous script to the millions of spent casings littering the screen, The Last Stand stands, staggers and then falls as Ahnold's nadir.(And the blu-ray is terrible as well, not one special feature or commentary. Message to studios: trailers are NOT special features!)Nothing makes sense in The Last Stand in any way, which would be fine if it wasn't trying to. But the Govanata is taking semi-serious aim here at the Mexican drug cartels, political correctness, feds and a bunch of other things, and misses on almost every count. The cartels are apparently staffed and headed by Europeans; the feds and other branches of Arizona law enforcement don't know how to get to the Arizona border within a few hours even when huge shootouts erupt (well, that might be true); guys like Knoxville have insanely felonius machine guns ready to go at any moment, and a few thousand rounds to stick in them; and many other truly nonsensical plot points. I know, it's all supposed to be crazy fun, but if Arnie wants to get political about it all, which he does here, portraying himself as a Clint/Gary Cooper kind of sheriff saving the American Way, he could at least make a stab at semi-believability. You know, like Mr. Freeze.And why is Forest Whittaker in this? He plays it as he always does, painfully serious, and derails the possible comedy while highlighting how sadly unserious this whole enterprise is. Strange casting choice. "Ah vant to act with a SEERIOUS acta!"The most notable thing to me was that TLS is the first Ahnold film where he not only doesn't flirt with women, but goes out of his way to barely notice them at all in a male-female sort of way. Still stinging from his bonking-the-maid scandal, the mighty Schwarz is merely polite to every woman in the film. Ahnold the Gelded! It's hard to see him now and not think of the cigar-chomping maid-bonking Governator, no matter how hard he tries to polish his image, such as it is.Maybe the worst moments here are when Ahnold pauses and almost yells at us, "Ahm goin to make anotha classic Ahnold statement nowww, pleeez listen und then loff und cheer like you should!". Then he'll utter something typically Ahnold...but the old get-in-tha-choppa magic is gone, and now it just feels overdone with the humor removed. Hasta la vista, Arnie.All in all, I expected a hare-brained adventure and that's what this is, except the hare is a tiny little buuny wabbit with a bwain the size of a pea. Nothing really works except Knoxville, who plays his role purely for laughs with the sort of mindless glee and disregard for reality that the whole movie should have had. Instead, it takes itself too seriously times ten and ends up being just plain stupid.Poor Ahnold. He probably won't get the Oscar for this one either.If he's smart he'll give up action and politics and stick to the comedy, where he truly belongs.Imagine if Mr. Freeze went to the melting polar ice caps.Extremely heavily armed, of course. And all the women in parkas.

reviewText: Arnold is getting just a little bit old to be making action movies, but in this movie he is supposed to be an aging sheriff in a small town an it works. What can I say, this is an action movie. The first half of the movie is spent developing the characters and plot. The second half of the movie is the unfolding of the plot and all of the action. In my opinion there are too many secondary characters and none of them gets fully developed in this movie. Arnold has no love interest or family in this movie. So all you are really left with is the action. This is the kind of movie that you really only want to watch once, so I'm not sure if investing in a Blu-Ray disc is the best idea. If I had it to do over, I would just rent the movie from Netflix or Red Box. This movie and its plot are no where near the quality of movies such as the "Die Hard" or "Lethal Weapon" series. The problem for Arnold is that he is getting too old to play the muscle bound protector that saves the world and that is all he really has to offer. I like Arnold, but I'm afraid he I going to have to develop some acting skills or find some new stories that fit his aging character if he is to continue to put out movies.

reviewText: What surprised in screening this was that a even well seasoned performer, with a limited but highly successful schtick, can get rusty over time.Arnold, already infamous for his market focused craft, was skilled enough to pull off the specific roles that fit his abilities. But one can really see the oxide that had built up over the 10 years between full-time gigs. It seemed that, while heading a state government, the past decade of clamping down his natural, and sometimes overbearingly positive, personality had a more profound and lingering effect.In this production, he plays a sheriff in a small Southern California town that is way off the beaten track. The former LA special services cop has found peace and serenity dealing with the mundanity of parking violations and the occasional drunk. Unbeknownst to him - his life and the lives of the residents are about to be upended by an escaped drug lord intent on driving through their land into Mexico and freedom from US law enforcement.Aided by a cadre of hardcore private contractors who have been hired to, quite literally, clear a path - can the sheriff stop the determined felon and his band of heavily armed mercenaries with just a handful of backwater officers? Utilizing one of Arnie's trademark menacing squinty-eyed quips, "I've got an idea."The tiresome and trite opening of this flick is happily forgotten when the action elements pick up steam a little past a third of the way in. And despite the fanciful (read ludicrous) premise of the screenplay, was the only reason I stuck with it to the end.Overall, entertaining enough and worth the one-time screening. But anyone expecting an Arnie movie of old will be disappointed. In spite of the very enjoyable high speed chase sequences, there just wasn't enough invested in establishing the characters beyond their perfunctory sketchy outline. One has to put that onus on Korean director Jee-woon Kim. Like many non-western directors, they often struggle to successfully transplant, translate and transform their skills to and for the US palette. More so given that this was his very first production outside his country.Hopefully, Arnie works on a better vehicle with a more proven director.Movie Notes:- To the best of my knowledge, this is only the second time a large industrial magnet is used to hijack an armored transport in a film. One of my all-time favorite über classic comedies - the original 1979 version ofThe In-Laws.- How about that cameo Conan sword and pose? Nice!  :-D- As 2013 marks his (non-cameo) featured return to the big show - and in keeping with their friendly feud - I would say that Sly Stallone's recent 'Bullet To The Head' is a tad better and a bit more enjoyable production. But that opinion might be jaded because I have a thing for Sarah Shahi. <g>Personal Note:- Interestingly, I'm actually a fan of Johnny Knoxville. Although generally dismissed as an actor, I find him to be a solid performer with hints that he has a much wider range than his film resume suggests. Most certainly better than any number of robotic six-pack pretty boys from a wide array of reality-tv programs wanting to move onto the silver screen.

reviewText: Starring Arnold Schwarzenegger, Forest Whitaker, Johnny Knoxville, Rodrigo Santoro. Jaimie Alexander and lots of other people, this is absolutely the best movie ever made by a former governor of California. Or any former governor.I’m not a very intellectual movie reviewer. That’s just as well, since there is nothing intellectual about this movie.It’s pretty good. Lots of shooting. Blood spurting. Vicious bad guys. It has the grace to not take itself too seriously, with enough humorous moments and entirely predictable but nonetheless funny lines to make it easy to watch.“I’m The Sheriff!” growls Arnold and by golly, he is, though Garry and I simultaneously pointed out that he used to be The Governor.There are a lot of car chases … or maybe not really chases. More accurately, it is exceptionally good stunt driving. They actually did some stunts I’ve never seen before and I really thought I’d seen them all.Plot? Oh, right. Plot. Okay. Think “High Noon” with a strong whiff of “Terminator.” Or any western movie where the sheriff stands up to some incredibly evil guys and whups their collective asses with the help of his faithful deputies and one old lady with a shot-gun. You’ll be glad to know that Arnold Schwarzenegger, senior citizen, ex-governor gets shot, stabbed and beat up, but walks away proudly in the end. Not into the sunset, but into the local diner. Irv’s Diner. He's not even bleeding!Killing people and catching malevolent drug lords gives him an appetite. I’m sorry I forgot to buy popcorn. It’s a beautiful, deeply touching, moment.If you need a violence fix, this is a pretty good choice. It’s well made. Moves right along. Some great artillery and the aforementioned stunt driving.
summary: BEST MOVIE EVER STARRING A FORMER GOVERNOR

reviewText: ARNOLD SCHWARZENEGGER has always been one of the old school power hero's. For along time he and SYLVESTER STALLONE were the go to guys when it comes to the action packed 'shoot em up' type of movie. But as the years have gone buy new faces like Farrell, Vin Decil, Will Smith, etc. have filled the theaters. But Arnold comes roaring back after a decade of hiatus to pull off a very decent movie! reviewText: The Last Stand is a good choice of a movie to watch on a slow friday or saturday night.  Its entertaining, its arnolds first full feature since returning from politics and it delivers some of the basic material you would expect.At times, it feels as though there are two different movies going on at the same time here, one involving arnold and then another involving criminals trying to get another criminal free from a las vegas jail.  In between there are tons of shots of the open desert, in between nevada and arizona, in the fiction town of Somerton.  Yes, I looked it up on google maps, and its not there, but I'm pretty sure it is.....Anyways, arnold plays the typical hero/s**t-kicker type, this time he's the old and tired sheriff of Somerton, just trying to enjoy his "day off"(repeated over and over and shown in the trailer, to make sure you know he's more like a retiree.  Meanwhile the bad guys plan to come through the town and get into mexico, because once you make it over that hill, you've made it.Typical fare in between all that, including minor car chases/crashes, gunplay and "this is my town", lets "standown", etc....  The action scenes will you keep you entertained, I enjoyed the desert setting and overall its a decent action story, just nothing superior to any of his early films.  The movie also has a part played by Johnny Knoxville, this time as a local who is a little nutty, but also character who becomes needed when the good guys need to borrow his gun stash.If you like somewhat dumb action movies, with little complex thinking involved this is your flick.  If you are not familiar with arnold's movies, also checkout his movie Junior.
summary: The Last Stand is a good choice for a friday

reviewText: After watching Arnold in last year's action ensemble "The Expendables 2" I had to wonder if he could still carry a film after years of being Governor, this film put that fear to rest, Arnold definately doesn't shy away from the fact that he is older now, & that is what makes his character so likable, also Arnold doesn't mind letting the supporting cast have equal screen time, everyone from Forrest Whittaker as a F.B.I. agent chasing a dangerous drug lord to the drug lord himself making his getaway in a super fast Corvette to Johnny Knoxville as a guy who helps Arnold all get to shine here, as Arnold who is a small town sherriff knows that the drug lord will soon be passing through his town that soon becomes a battleground as the drug lord's lackeys try to ensure his safe passage through, Arnold & his deputies take them all on, there is one scene where Arnold is thrown through a window & some residents ask him how he feels, his reply "old!"....once again Arnold doesn't let us forget he is older now, but he still has it, the one-liners & all, I really liked this film a lot better than I thought I would, If you are a true Arnold fan, this is a must have!

reviewText: Other than the fact that Arnold is a little older and moves a little slower (and makes jokes about being old and not being able to eat yummy  double bacon and double cheddar omelets, apparently a specialty in his town), the movie is a rocket ride that doesn't disappoint. The plot is a bit convoluted...a drug dealer in a race to the Mexican border, which means he has to pass through Arnie's turf. Forest Whitaker appears as FBI Agent John Bannister and basically does what he does in 85 of all his other movies...look really concerned and give a lot of orders. Peter Stormare (Fargo / Big Lebowski) is another bad guy who ramps up the fun just by being Peter Stormare. Johnny Knoxville adds comic relief to the action. Veteran character actor Luis Guzmán (you'll recognize him immediately) does a brilliant turn as Arnie's deputy...he wants no part of what's about to come down and doesn't hesitate when it comes to saying it. Lovers of the Chevrolet Camaro will be heartbroken during the cornfield scene, but the moment this pristine red beauty appears on screen you know it's not just going to spend the entire film parked in the red zone. Is this as great as Arnie's first wave of classic action films? No, but he can still deliver the goods, and he is still undeniably fun to watch on screen. The plot is a bit of a mess and other than Whitaker, whose role could have been played by anyone, the cast is fun. If you like car chases, gunfire, and explosions, you've come to the right place. The movie was MUCH better than I'd expected. Recommended.

reviewText: The Last Stand was supposed to me Arnold Schwarzenegger’s big comeback, but instead it turned out to be a big bomb and a movie that nobody remembers.  Honestly, I can see why.  Last Stand is a very generic action film with Arnold starring in it.  It is quite boring, the characters are quite lame, most of the performances missed the mark, and Arnold seemed like he was sleepwalking throughout the entire film.The plot is very simple.  An escape convict named Cortez has escaped from FBI custody and is heading for the town of Summerton Junction.  It is now up to Sherif Ray Owens (Arnold Schwarzenegger) and his deputies to stop him and his friends.  The plot is very straight-forward, which I do not mind if the movie is fun and the characters are enjoyable but that is not really the case.Arnold really has no energy here.  He just seemed like he was on auto-pilot, and he had no memorable lines.  I know he is getting older but I have seen him give better performances lately.  He gave a much better performance in Escape Plan.  The other actors did not do a great job either.  Everyone either underacts or overacts their lines, particularly the FBI boss played by Forest Whitaker.  He is supposed to be intimidating but he just comes off as so over-the-top in this that I could not take him seriously.  The only actor who does a decent job is Jaimie Alexander who plays the female deputy.  She is one of the best actresses working today and deserves more jobs.  She plays the only somewhat decent character too.  The villains are one-note, which would be fine if the movie was fun and the good guys were fun, but that is not the case.The only saving grace was that some of the action scenes are well-done.  I like that that this is a hard R and they do not pull punches with the violence.  They go for PG-13 a lot lately to make the film more marketable.  Some of the action scenes particularly the action scene at the end was quite good.  However I do not think there were enough action scenes.  The beginning of the film was very slow and boring.  A slow build is fine if the characters are fun, but they’re not.  Also much of the film seemed to be dedicated to promoting cars.  A good portion of this film felt like a car commercial.  It was horrible.Overall, The Last stand is a forgettable action film.  It had some fun action scenes, but the characters are nothing, the villain is nothing, only a couple people gave a good performance, Arnold is on auto-pilot, and much of the film felt like a car commercial.  I can see why no one saw this film when it came out and why it is now forgotten.  The film is good as a time-waster and not much else.
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: I remember weeks ago seeing back-to-back trailers for this film and Sylvester Stallone's "Bullet to the Head." Sly's film looked ridiculous and stupid, not to mention he is after thugs that took his daughter. How original. But then Arnold's movie trailer comes on and it seems pretty clear we are going to get good guys and bad guys in an unlikely shoot-out, but damn if it doesn't look like fun. And damn if it isn't.Schwarzenegger plays Sheriff Ray Owens, a small town cop on the Arizona-Mexico border. Coming his way from Las Vegas is an escaped cartel boss (Eduardo Noriega) in a souped-up Corvette ZR-1. In a ridiculous and convoluted scenario, this occurs during a transfer supervised by FBI agent John Bannister played by Forest Whitaker in a performance about as lame as his character's management of the transfer. Maybe Whitaker just couldn't understand director Jee-woon Kim's instructions.The fun really starts when Cortez (Noriega) approaches the border town. You see Cortez is also a professional race car driver. Think about it. In an earlier set up, Cortez has sent a cadre of henchmen ahead to prepare a portable bridge over a ravine into Mexico. Since everyone is out of town at a football game, the sheriff will have to defend their border with an out-of-shape deputy (Luis Guzman), another pair of deputies new to the job (Zach Gilford and Jaimie Alexander), the town drunk/ Iraq War veteran (Rodrigo Santoro) and town gadfly (Johnny Knoxville).Arnold is at his self-deprecating best as the tired veteran of the L. A. police force just looking for a little quiet time. The film is exactly what it promises, nothing more. It's fun.
summary: 3 1/2 stars for a fun time with Arnold back in action

reviewText: The Last Stand is a classic action movie. It takes place in a little town in Arizona called Sommerton Junction. Arnold plays the sheriff of the small town, who used to be in the LAPD narcotic division, but after a botched operation he decides to take on a job that has a little less excitement, but all that changes when a drug cartel kingpin named Gabriel Cortez escapes from FBI custody a heads straight for his quiet little town. Cortez's men take up shop in the small town and begin working on building a bridge over the narrow canyon, so that Cortez can get across the border and out of the reach of the FBI, but once Owens (Schwarzenegger) pieces together what is going on gathers up what deputies he has, along with deputizing the town drunk/war veteran Frank Martinez played by Rodrigo Santoro and the owner of the Dinkum Firearm and Historic Weapon Museum Lewis Dinkum played by none other than Johnny Knoxville, and make a stand against Cortez and his men.There is plenty of speed, crazy driving stunts and bullets for any action fan, with some humor thrown in to wrap it up nicely. Arnold may not be in tip top form, but he still has absolutely no problem carrying a movie, and it is great to see him back in action. For any fan of action flicks or Arnold this is a must see movie.So get your popcorn and soda ready than strap yourself in for The Last Stand!

reviewText: Dirty, gritty, over the top and darkly hilarious. This movie has everything an action movie should have. Schwarzenegger proves yet again why he is the face of the over the top fun. There's gatling guns, 200 mph car chases, gun fights every twenty minutes and down home honest living. By the end of this movie I was literally audible with excitement. The fight scenes will blow you away. We've had to deal with fight scenes that are so close you can't tell what's going on. Not with this movie, the camera work is absolutely perfect. The gore effects of gunshot wounds are actually realistic and the firepower is enough to satisfy any action fan. The dialogue is pretty well done, the story line is simple but perfect for an action flick, the soundtrack is rocking and the stylized cinematography is great.I really can't express how much I loved this movie. Easily one of Schwarzenegger's best and easily one of the best to come out this year.
summary: This is why action movies were made

reviewText: Spaghetti Western & a bit tongue & cheek.  The start is slow and painful at times, but as the movie moves on, there are parts that are fun & funny. The 1 horse town & it's folks are great. It starts a bit obvious and the editing is choppy.  Arnold aside, this movie has great car chases, guns & a some good fights.  There is some character development and the film works to incorporate several innovative themes from other action movies. The 2 things I like in the film are the guns & the hand to hand combat scenes.  The villain is absolutely fabulous, Arnold is good here and the other characters were perfect.  With what is going on in our nation today with 2nd amendment issues & border crossings, this film doesn't take itself seriously.  Not a musts see, but fun.  Also, the "R" rating is for language.  There is some gruesome violence if only to make the point.

reviewText: I'm not sure what I was expecting from this film. Every other movie I've seen where they drag out some aging action star has been pretty bad, with the predictable self-deprecating remarks, tired catch phrases, and the star looking vaguely lost. This one is not as bad as some, but it feels more like product than like something anybody involved actually cared about. The writing is lazy overall, though there are some mildly witty exchanges between some characters. Some of the action sequences have creative energy and a freshness to them, too, and the film has the saving grace of not taking itself too seriously. But overall, the film is just OK. You won't feel like you lost 90 minutes of your life, but if you're like me, you'll end up wishing for more.
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: Well, OK... it's Arnie alright, and funny and gritty as we have come to love him... so from that angle, I had a fun time watching.However, it is strongly recommended to leave your logical, thinking brain at the door! This is the story of a jail break. A very dangerous criminal is being transferred to another prison facility, and the FBI staff wants to make sure that this will not end up being a botched operation. They know that the crime organization in Mexico wants its boss back, if they can help it.Suffice it to say that everybody's fears will come true, and off we go on a bloody and merry chase to catch our fugitive. There'll be shootings galore and blunders by the FBI all over the place. The entire escape plan - to say it mildly - must have been concocted by a bunch of cowboy guys whose main objective was to have as many opportunities to goof it up as possible, and do everything the complicated, illogical, hard way! If a chick had devised this plan, she would have just used a plane and crossed that border to Mexico in the air, and bingo, done. Very pragmatically, simple and effective.But, of course, then there would not have been this movie! So just sit back, let everything go, laugh at the funny characters, of which there are a handful, and take it for what it is: guys-style, fight-pickin' fun!
summary: and funny and gritty as we have come to love him

reviewText: "The Last Stand" (2013 release; 107 min.) brings the return of Arnold as a movie headliner (after a couple of teasers as a minor role in "The Expendables" movies), and the plot, as it is, is fairly straight-forward and easy to digest. The leader of a Mexican drug cartel is sprung from jail in Las Vegas, and is speeding down towards the Mexican border in a souped-up Corvette ZR1 (the other co-star of the movie). The last thing standing between him and freedom in Mexico is a small border town in Arizona, where Arnold is the Sheriff and his staff is small.Several comments: the plot is totally secondary to the action, and at that level, the movie delivers, period. There is hardly any lull in the movie. The highlight for me personnaly was the car chase between Arnold and the Mexican drig lord in the Arizona cornfield, which is staged beautifully, almost like a ballet of cars. Kudos to Korean director Jee-woon Kim who knows a thing or two about action movies but makes his Hollywood debut with this one. Well done. As to Arnold, he has definitely aged since his last major starring role in 2003 (Terminator 3), but he hasn't lost his sense of humor. When the Mexican drug lord at the very end tries to bribe Arnold with multi-millions, Arnold responds (in full Arnold-accent): "You make us immigrants look bad!" I just had to laugh out loud at that (I'm a first generation immigrant from Europe myself).This movie outright bombed at the box office last weekend. I almost didn't go see it but then several things changed my mind: both Entertainment Weekly and the Financial Times (whose movie reviewers I respect a great amount) gave it strong reviews, and my 26 yr. old son gave it 2 thumbs up after he saw it with his friends last weekend. I decided to check it out. So glad I did. There is nothing "revolutionary" about this movie, but it's mindless entertainment and a quality action movie, period. Now all we need is for Arnold to make another "Terminator" movie (keeping fingers crossed).

reviewText: Bad acting and a predictable plot fortunately doesn't detract too much from a otherwise enjoyable flick. The baddies getaway car, a Chevrolet ZR-1 is Knight Rider reborn. This one of a kind conveyance is faster than a speeding bullet (or helicopter in this case), equipped with infrared (which apparently the FBI doesn't have), an unlimited fuel tank allowing the car to travel at 200 mph all night without refuelling, truck flipping technology with minimal paint damage and off road capabilities which would put any 4x4 to shame.Forest Whittaker wins the most unconvincing character award with his portrayal as FBI Agent John Bannister. After losing a top drug lord on the way to jail, he's given full command on recapturing the evil Gabiel Gomez who believes that driving very fast and devastating road blocks wins hands down over obscurity. Maybe because of the Clint Eastwood accent, Bannister's bosses have complete misplaced faith in his abilities, which luckily Arnie puts right by destroying the town he's Sheriff of in order to apprehend the bad guys. All that aside, there are some great action scenes and a feeling of the old cowboy movies of yesteryear with a fusion of the spaghetti westerns with greats like Rio Bravo. Not one for the squeamish, there are lots of CGI blood effects.

reviewText: I've always like Arnold movies and purchased several over the years. We watched this one, even though the previews looked terrible when it came out in the theaters, because it had 3 1/2 stars on Amazon. It was embarrassing to watch such a poorly-written, poorly-directed and poorly-acted film.The writers never really decided whether to make this a more serious film or some sort of slap-stick comedy and came out with a horrible mix of both.Then tried to give Arnold some one-liners the caliber of "hasta la vista baby" or others. He looked like he was reading one-liners while they, for no particular reason, would zoom in on his face while he said them.Then there is the issue of his physical appearance/abilities now. Nothing he did physically seemed believable in his condition. It was sad to watch.Forest Whitaker is also one of my favorite actors but he looked like some sort of over-acting idiot with one expression: "WTF am I doing in this movie!?!"The ending credits seemed to be some sort of "Last Action Hero" (a movie I loved and found very fun to watch) attempt gone bad.I can't recommend this film.

reviewText: Four SURPRISING Stars! Enjoyable Arnold Schwarzenegger action flick. For those of us who skipped this movie, and I'm one, give it another consideration. Sommerton Junction, Arizona is a sleepy border town with so little crime one of the deputies wants a transfer to Los Angeles PD. Act I, Sommerton, AZ: all is calm and quiet, except for visiting drivers of a strange 18 wheel truck. Act II, Las Vegas, NV: a daring escape by a ruthless criminal. Act III, convergence of plots, with hot sports cars in the middle of it all. Amid the bullets and bombs, Arnold gets a chance to do some serious, sensitive acting scenes as a beer-swigging, peace-loving Sheriff Ray Owens who is on his day off when trouble arrives in his town. This movie has some great chase scenes featuring a form of the director's famous `trunk cam shots' and ends with an unusual climatic chase scene and a great showdown in a unique place. Arnold Schwarzenegger, Forest Whitaker, Eduardo Noriega, Johnny Knoxville, Rodrigo Santoro, Jaimie Alexander ("Lady Sif" from the Marvel movies and TV show), Genesis Rodriguez (from "Man of a Ledge"), and well-known character actor Luis Guzman. Violence, gore, and profanity. Directed by Kim, Jee-Woon. Bring on the next "Terminator" movie: even at age 66, Arnold is ready. Very Definitely Recommended for action and Arnold fans. Four ACTION-PACKED Stars! (Amazon Prime Video; Time-1:48)
summary: ENJOYABLE ACTION FLICK: ARNOLD IS A TOUGH ARIZONA SHERIFF ON HIS DAY OFF
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: I am surprised that this movie didn't do better at the box office, but I think it was up against stiff competition at the time.  I think it was a really good movie and I sure wouldn't mind seeing it again and owning it.  Arnold's still got it!  A lot of good action with unlikely heroes....some incredible car chase scenes... good plot, and some good laughs, too.  I really wasn't expecting to like it as much as I did, but was pleasantly surprised!  Way to go, Arnold!!! Looking forward to your next project!
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: If you've seen the trailer, there's no spoilers here.Arnold and his town cronies were dynamic, had great character and some whispers of conflict.  Then came the criminal transport.  That ENTIRE aspect of the movie felt tacked on as an after thought.  Based upon the characters, it seemed like what "should've" been the story is something like an ex-con arrested by Schwarzenneger's character moves into that sleepy border town to use it for running people, guns, drugs... and then Schwarzenneger makes a "Last Stand" to stop him.  Instead some random Gov't Agent decides for random reasons to move a criminal from a "high security" prison to another "high security" prison by using very "low security" transportation.  Minor SPOILER:  At one point the Gov't agent says, "we're going to go real quiet, under the radar"  Then a convoy of like 20 black Gov't SUVs roar down the road!  Definitely NOT quiet and under the radar.  :-\
summary: Should've left out the arch criminal...

reviewText: I watched this flick out of nostalgia for the "good old times" when I used to watch the old schwarzy movies like Conan or Predator... or the classic Terminator saga..but I regret I did.. this movie is more stupid then Commando and hey, it's not even the 80s anymore... I would even let the heavily unrealistic initial escape of the "bad guy" ( a drug dealer megaboss..) go, but then.. this guy getting on the highway on a super duper corvette all the way down to mexico and the FBI being unable to stop him? And does he really need an assault bridge to be built for him to cross a little canyon? And all the FBI can do is send a couple cars that get crushed by his corvette ...so that we can have a "modern cowboy scene" ? Come on.. who writes this stuff?The best that can be said about this flick is that it is a huge commercial for firearms and a time sink for morons..Even the classical schwarzenegger "cheesy but fun and quirky" acting is off.. like he himself doesn't really believe in what he's doing.. or maybe he's just become too dry and boring after meddling with politics (and what politics..)Couldn't you wait for something at least a little more decent, Schwarzy?

reviewText: This is a difficult movie to review. If you consider it to be just a beer and pizza type of Western Comedy then you will be very entertained. It is almost a parody of "High Noon" with the world's most violent drug lord descending on a small Texas border town and only Arnold Schwarzenegger can save the day. The problem is that the movie does take itself seriously at times in the style of "Criminal Minds". The FBI Agents even use one of those cool FBI luxury jets. This was a big mistake because it makes all law enforcement look like Keystone Cops and Arnold Schwarzenegger looks like a nursing home resident who wanted one last day on the job before retiring. The FBI was notified that the drug lord was going to Arnold Schwarzenegger's town so they send a SWAT team. The problem is that the entire SWAT team fits into JUST 2 VEHICLES! This is Arnold Schwarzenegger's backup for the most violent drug lord in the world! Even when the FBI realizes that they did not send enough manpower they all get into the luxury jet and then drive to the town in - you guessed it - JUST 2 VEHICLES! No National Guard, no Border Patrol, no State Police, no Military.If you want a Western Comedy then this is it. But if you are a "Criminal Minds" type then this movie is a big embarrassment. Arnold Schwarzenegger has a few good lines like - "You make all of us immigrants look bad". And I loved seeing him driving into town at the end in the newly converted convertible.Be prepared. The dialogue is very low volume and the sound effects are at ear piercing volume.
summary: I had a few problems with it.

reviewText: ...Kim Jee Won, the director, asks for a lot of suspended belief. There are many excellent stunts, which is to be expected I reckon with Johnny Knoxville on board, but the gun battles remind me of the ones I saw as a kid on TV's The A-Team. You know the ones, with people standing out in the open, firing automatic weapons at one another....and largely missing. Cars being blown up right next to people....and they survive. Arnie...poor old aged Arnie, getting veins slashed, getting shot, getting stabbed ---and still fighting like he did in the Commando. Really?The sad thing is this movie has a good cast. Forest Whitaker is a great actor, but in this, his talent is squelched to the ninth degree. Luis Guzman is also a seasoned actor who's real talent is not evident here. It all comes off like a TV action show with a few blood and gut shots thrown in to make it feel like a movie.And then the cars?  What?  Come ON!  I can take you back to the 1970's and THE FRENCH CONNECTION and you will see a far better, more exciting car chase sequence than in this movie. That is sad.Apparently, this was just an advertisement for Chevy --I reckon Obama Motors needs the publicity since The Volt is pretty much SUNK!As far as Arnie goes, please, get out while you are somewhat ahead. You destroyed CALI-FOR-NI-YUH....and now this???Let this be, indeed, your LAST STAND!
summary: Middle of the Road on this one. Some Blood and Action but.....

reviewText: The Last Stand(released Jan/13)stars,among others,Arnold Schwarzenegger,Forest Whitaker,Johnny Knoxville,Peter Stormare,Rodrigo Santoro,Eduardo Noriega and Luis Guzman.This film marks Arnold's return to movie making on his own.It has a good supporting cast and the action comes hard and heavy and often.The story finds an ex L.A.policeman(Arnold) playing sheriff in a small town by the name of Somerton Junction,Az.The other concurrent plot running is an escaped cartel member by the name of Cortez(Noriega)trying desperately to get across the border into Mexico.His escape from the FBI was quite daring and well planned,and he has seemingly thought of everything and paid handsomely to see that it is followed through.When Arnold and his deputies find a murdered farmer just outside of Somerton,they investigate further and accidentally stumble upon a group of hired thugs building a temporary bridge across a canyon that separate Arizona from Mexico.In the firefight that ensues one of Arnold's deputies gets killed.In the meantime the head of the FBI unit trying to nab the suspect(Whittaker)re-routes personnel to Somerton upon learning of the goings on there.His men never reach Somerton as they're killed before they ever reach it by Cortez in his high powered car.It all comes down to Arnold,two of his deputies left and two friends whom he deputises.This is the titled"last stand" and Arnold and the crew make use of every vehicle and bullet they can scrounge up.The first to arrive is the thugs they first encountered building the bridge.Over a half dozen arrive and start shooting everything in sight.Arnold comes back with an old vintage machine gun and the game,as they say,is on.Shot is traded for shot and a lot of folks get killed,but Arnold and company stand fast.Just as they have that situation under control,in zooms Cortez in his car and Arnold takes off in pursuit.As Cortez tries to head for the bridge Arnold forces him off the road and into a corn field.After a hectic chase there both end up crashing into a parked farmer's combine.After the dust clears Cortex hops it for the bridge.As he arrives who should be standing in the middle but Arnie,of course.Cortez tries to buy him off but Arnold is having none of it.They wrestle and punch,and punch and wrestle and Arnold of course is victorious,as he walks/pulls Cortez behind his car all the way back into town.The town is saved,new friendships are born and Arnold lives to sheriff another day.The film starts off a little slow as it introduces the two ultimately diverging plots but eventually the movies gets its legs and things start to slowly but surely get hot and heavy.The action ebbs and flows throughout the film and helps keep the picture on the beam.Arnold is certainly showing his age and has gained some pounds around the middle,but he still has what it takes.I should mention a scene in the film that shows all too briefly Arnold's acting ability.It is where his deputy is rushed to the hospital,but as soon as Arnold opens up the back seat he broken heartedly says"Johnny".We don't even have to see Johnny to know what has happened.The tone of his voice combined with his sincere look is one of the few moments that I can say I have seen Arnold REALLY act in a dramatic fashion.It was quite touching.Also it is nice to finally see good old supporting actor Luis Guzman make it through a movie and not get killed within the first 30 minutes.He WAS wounded but he did pull through.Peter Stormare does what he does best as the real bad guy in this film.And Johnny Knoxville,a gun freak,becomes becomes Arnold's Joxer to his Xena.Technically speaking the film is in its w/s a/r of 1:85:1 and is clear and crisp.Extras abound with four featurettes,commentary and extended and deleted scenes.All in all The Last Stand marks a good return to Arnold's native land of action,in a good film chock full of fights,car chases and lots and lots of gun fighting.Arnold even gets to stretch and use some of those long dormant acting chops of his.Worth a look,or two or three. Recommended.3 1/2 stars.

reviewText: Wow, Arnold being gone for all these years makes seeing him now really a shocker.  Still, he has that certain charisma, and charm, that made him popular in the 80's and 90's.  I always appreciate when actors show their age, and aren't afraid to cop to a bit of aches and pains.  Arnold does that here, and it makes him more believable, and more fun to watch.  Of course, the movie is full of incredibly hokey stunts, like the bad guy spinning a full 180 degree turn, stomping the brakes in front of a SWAT vehicle, and having it run right up the front and over (doing the obligatory flip, in the process).  It's even more unbelievable when you realize that the vehicle is a Vet, which are made of fiberglass, and disintegrate when the wind blows too hard.  Driving away with just a few scratches was rather comical.All-in-all, I enjoyed seeing Mr. S. on the screen again.  He hasn't lost his timing, or his comedic chops, and I respect his body of work for what it is, pure escapism and fun.  Good to see you again Arnold.

reviewText: At first glance, Kim Jee-Woon's "The Last Stand" feels a bit like a pity-flick handed to the aging Arnold Schwarzenegger for all his years of service to the industry (not to mention the state of California). Yet, the movie is so happy-go-lucky in its tone and so shamelessly brazen in its goofiness that the viewer actually has a hard time disliking it.Andrew Knauer's rather astonishing everything-but-the-kitchen-sink screenplay features the former governor as the bone-creaking sheriff of a sleepy Arizona border town who's job it becomes to prevent an escaped convict in a turbo-charged race car from using his town as a crossing point into Mexico - something the FBI itself proves incapable of doing.The film seems to exist in two completely separate spheres simultaneously - which is both its biggest charm and its greatest drawback. The sheriff leads a team of bumbling cops and petty criminals - who quite literally can't shoot straight - straight into the eye-teeth of a band of high-tech, take-no-prisoners, armed-to-the-teeth bad guys whose utter ruthlessness makes the Corleone family look like the Waltons. This results in a rather uncomfortable mix of uber-violent action sequences and Keystone Kop buffoonery. The effect is not unlike what one would get if Walter White and Jesse Pinkman were portrayed by Fred Flintstone and Barney Rubble. Yet, somehow, at certain moments at least, the crazy thing kind of works, and the audience can't help pulling for it, especially when the movie itself seems as much of a scruffy underdog as the sheriff and his ragtag underlings.Ah well, at least the movie doesn't take itself too seriously, and the full-speed-ahead action rarely lets up.
summary: absurd action flick that's actually hard to dislike

reviewText: OK, I should have known this movie would be bad when the Sheriff asks a local resident for his gun 'permits' and gets a stack handed to him.Ha Ha.. not.The plot makes it very clear that this is happening in AZ, which doesn't require any kind of permit to own a firearm. California scriptwriter ignorance showing through when it comes to a major plot point going forward.Besides the ignorance of the subject matter, the plot itself is ridiculous. It's based on the premise that only Arnold can stop a single car from driving all the way from Vegas to Mexico. ???Every hear of helicopters? Spike strips? Roadblocks with Jersey barriers?The characters are so one dimensional you can see right past them. The plot 'twists' are either unsurprising or pointless, and the 'humor' isn't.Keep clear of this junk, it's not even a good 'mindless' action movie.

reviewText: Arnie is back!!! And he has still got it, this is an awesome comeback for the king of action movies, he maybe getting old but he's still very entertaining, this movie has a simple yet cool story about an escaped prisoner who picks the wrong town to go through while plotting his escape, there is plenty of bloody violence in this movie which is surprising for its 15 cert! The rest of the cast is good, Johnny Knoxville is funny and entertaining as usual, the movie has its comedy side which works well, overall it's a great start for Arnie and a must for fans, he will be standing a lot longer yet.

reviewText: Although much of this was predictable, it was quite entertaining.  When one of his deputies takes a bullet, the sheriff knows he is outmanned, so he calls the FBI for back-up.  But they don't believe him, so when the drug dealers pass through the small sleepy border town of Summerton, Arizona on their way to Mexico, they run into a surprisingly effective blockade.  Once again, Arnold give the audience a memorable line:  "Welcome to Summerton."

Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: Arnold Schwarzenegger promised he'd be back and now he is following his stint as governor of California  In the Last Stand, in his first starring role in nearly a decade, but it isn't all it should be as a comeback vehicle, don't get me wrong, it's good to have the big guy back on the big screen where he belongs, but the Last Stand ends up being only a modest return and a little bit of a disappointment.As a movie, the Last Stand plays as a movie at least a two decades or more out of step with current audiences. It is a modern day western that hits all the lazy western clichés. It's actually little more than a contemporary version of Rio Bravo with Arnie as John Wayne and Johnny Knoxville as Walter Brennan, it even has a town drunk who's redeemed by standing tall alongside Schwarzenegger.The movie also couldn't have come at a worst time, with gun control as a hot bed issue. The Last Stand has enough of a pro-gun stance to please any card carrying member of the NRA. Set in an Arizona border town where everyone is packing heat and is either a redneck or a hillbilly.The Last Stand has about three story threads running through it. The first is the already mentioned neo-western starring Arnold. There is also one long continuous car chase involving an escaped fugitive, which looks like a very exciting car commercial, but a somethat boring movie. Then there is the counter point sub plot with Forrest Whitaker as a dogged FBI agent hunting said fugitive and having lots of unconving discourse, this is easily the least satisfying part of the movie.Schwarzenegger plays Ray Owen, a would-be Arizona cowboy who's actually a former L.A. narcotics officer. The role was originally written for Liam Neeson, it should have been written been written for Clint Eastwood. As long as you forget the details easily, like that name, Schwarzenegger actually does a very good job. He's as tough and strong as ever, but is more venerable that a lot of other movie tough guys, no longer a one man army or inhuman machine without feelings. He is still a strong and likable film presence, it's easy to forget just how good a movie star or even a good actor that he really is.It is an enthusiastic occasionally laughable shoot 'em up, but very much a forgettable "B" movie. Not completely unsatisfying, but not the triumphant return for Arnold Schwarzenegger. If anything it serves as a fearsome warning that a lot of these aging action stars are not only long in the tooth, but out of touch with contemporary values.The Last Stand is the English language debut of Jee-Won Kim. A South Korean director who's filmography, up to this point, has been very impressive. As  the director of the eerie horror film A Tale of Two Sisters, the brutal revenge thriller I Saw the Devil and the wonderfully giddy fun "teriyaki style western" the God, the Bad and the Weird. Jee-won gave lots of hope for this film, but he seems to be stifled by American filmmaking. I sincerely hope that this great talent does not find himself bogged down by formulaic action movies in the way that the equally fine director John Woo was.At least the Last Stand has a mostly game supporting cast including the excellent Spanish actor Eduardo Noriega as the central bad guy, but it is the wonderful Peter Stormare who is the film's main antagonist for the bulk of it's one hundred and three running time speaking with a southern fried American accent via way of Sweden. Also making a brief appearance is Harry Dean Stanton as a cantankerous shotgun wielding old codger. And as we know, no movie with Harry Dean Stanton in it can be all bad.However Johnny Knoxville serves as the unnecessary "comic relief" in a humorless role, fortunately he is not as much of a presence as his second billing would indicate. Also very much a sore spot is Luis Guzman, who was once a great character actor, but now just seems to be cast as annoying often cowardly dufases, this being no exception.Relative newcomers Jamie Alexander and Rodrigo Santoro stand out as Schwarzenegger's more serious deputies. Whitaker adds charisma in an undistinguished supporting role, but he is able to spout dialogue like "a psychopath in a Batmobile" with a straight face.Arnold Schwarzenegger is one of the great movie stars not just of the last thirty years, but of all-time and more than deserves a rightful film comeback, but this is not it. A half backed mostly uninteresting routine action flick. It's not Schwarzenegger's last stand, but if he doesn't choose his future projects more carefully he will continue to show his age in more ways than one. A modest failure in my opinion, but a failure none the less.see my reviews at moviezonemagazine.com
summary: not the comeback we had all hoped for

reviewText: Then you'll find something you wanted to see in this.  That said, it is not a very good movie, and not even a very good action movie.  Every stunt as been done before, some of then are even famous retreads to those of us who have been watching movies since the seventies ('Bullit' did it better).  But I sat down and clicked on Schwarzenegger and that's what I got. Same guy as the the 80s and 90s only more geriatric and stilted.  Any serious actor his age could have turned this into a better film, but, meh, I got what I clicked on.  I suggest you be at least three beers ahead before you even start, otherwise the stale, stumbling, badly paced/acted beginning will make you hit pause and never restart again.3 stars because I watched the whole thing.

reviewText: This movie is super, full of action and drama. Thank goodness, Arnold Schwarzenegger doesn't try to portray some young, buffed punk, but an older, tired sheriff who has moved to a small quiet town where he can finish his law enforcement years in peace and quiet after too many years in the city surrounded by gangs, drugs, and blood. And what town does a Mexican cartel decide to use to bring their recently escaped-from-jail drug lord boss? Arnold's, of course. And who isn't willing to stand by and let him through?  Arnold and his small-town deputies and friends. The last big battle is a bit of a stretch, but, it could be that way! Besides, no one ever accused Arnold of playing reality; but it's enjoyable and well-played.  I'll watch it again.

There was some humorous parts that could have been more developed, it would have been fun showing a little more interaction of these characters. That being said, as a viewer; I enjoyed when there was the interaction with these characters. Arnold is getting older, but I do believe his acting only keeps getting better. I do not whant to spoil anything about the movie so I will not mention scenes, but if you enjoy Arnold movies you will love this. The plot is far fetched, but its fun, enjoyable and will keep you entertained, and that's the intent.

reviewText: Arnold stars as a semi-retired Sheriff in a sleepy border town... Of course some super bad-guys need to get over the border and the only thing that stands in their way is Sheriff Arnold. Title: The Last Stand

reviewerName: The Movie Guy "Movies from A to Z"
reviewText: Arnold plays a small town sheriff after leaving an exciting life in the special forces, the LAPD, and as a cyborg. We get to meet the various characters in the town when suddenly a farmer is killed and his land is being prepared... Meanwhile...In LA, a high level cartel prisoner is being transported, a man who also drives race cars. Before Arnold can say, "I know what's coming" we know what's coming too minus a few details.Not since "Rocky V" has there been generated so much excitement about a comeback. Arnold plays Arnold, reminding me more of the "Ben Richards" Arnold. Perhaps it is because of his use of the word "negative." The characters and the over the top action make the film worth watching. Unfortunately the characters fell a little short on development and the action didn't go well with the script. The town confrontation scene was haphazardly done. Forest Whitaker plays an FBI man who should have been better developed and could have added some fun to the script. On the plus side, the script was "tight." It didn't give you any wasted scenes which didn't tie in later to the film. I like that aspect of writing.The day is saved by a gun enthusiast who have fallen out of grace for the moment. A worth while edition to an Arnold collection.Parental Guide: F-bombs (some with an accent). No sex or nudity.
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: glad to see Arnold back "in action." The storyline is not all that good but Arnold and his supporting cast do an excellent job in bumping it up a couple of notches. I think it is a good movie to add to your collection / library. Hope he makes more.

reviewText: I admit; I was intrigued to see if Arnold had lost his presence and cinema charisma -- he didn't and hasn't.  A very unique movie for him -- almost an allegory to his life.  He portrays a policeman who just wants to live his life quietly, but of course, something happens to upset that peace.An action movie with action, drama, comedy -- a complete movie.  Take note of the short on how this movie came about; you'll come to appreciate the movie more.
summary: Arnold's return to cinema; well worth it.
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: If each star is worth 20 points then this movie earns a solid 80% in my book. I am quite frugal when it comes to shelling out my money for 2 hours of entertainment  so I feel I have gotten my moneys worth seeing it on the big screen. There is plenty of old school action done very well, but I was not to crazy about the car chases/stunts. I can suspend belief for alot of things but the Corvette doing a complete 180 at breakneck speeds and continuing in reverse at 70(?) plus miles an hour is too ridiculous and unnecessary. Must have a bullet proof tranny and driveshaft! There was already plenty of cool stuff going on so the movie didn't need that "Fast and the Furious" style of automotive stunt work. However the car chase in the cornfield was pretty cool!Arnold plays a likeable guy and the villains are suitably ruthless enough that you want them to meet justice in an ugly way. My date thought the main villain was "hot" so of course I was glad to remind her that he was beat up by a 65 year old man. Granted it was a very large 65 year old man.This is the type of movie that will probably find its home next to "Roadhouse" on cable TV and I  do not mean that as an insult. Making a good action movie is an art form as legitimate making the next "Gone with the Wind." I do not see alot of credible actors that will be able to fill the the shoes of Arnold, Stallone or Chuck Norris . There isn't alot of character development going on in this movie, but at least it isn't paced like a video game(like the Crank movies.)It was good seeing Arnold back on the big screen again. If you enjoyed "Raw Deal" and "Commando" You will most likely not regret seeing this movie. I got exactly what I wanted and expected out of this flick. No Oscar awards here, but a good solid action flick!

reviewText: "We are not going to let that guy come through our town without a fight." After a mess up in the LAPD Ray Owens (Schwarzenegger) leaves to become the sheriff in the small town of Sommerton Junction. Nothing in the way of violence ever really happens and he likes it that way. When a drug kingpin begins his escape out of the country he gets past everyone and there is only one thing in the way of his escape, Sommerton and its Sheriff. Don't judge, but I was looking forward to watching this, mainly because I was wanting to mock it. I like Arnold but the movie looked cheesy from the previews. Going in with that expectation I was disappointed. There was quite a bit of action in this and some of the lines were funny but for the most part it was just too boring to even make fun of. I'm guessing because he's been away so long that Schwarzenegger was just looking for anything he could be in. If that's the case I forgive him. If he had hundreds of choices and he chose this one then...yeah. Overall, I couldn't get into it, too lame to even make fun of. I give it a C.
summary: Schwarzenegger's return to leading roles falls flat. Just a little too lame for me to get into. I say C.

reviewText: Arnold Schwarzenegger is back. "The Last Stand" is the 65-year-old former California governor's first starring vehicle in ten years since "Terminator 3: Rise of the Machines," but the film is also notable as the Korean director Jee-woon Kim's first Hollywood production. This is an unexpected collaboration - a veteran action star meets a cult filmmaker of "The Good, the Bad, the Weird" and "I Saw the Devil" - but it works.The story revolves around Ray Owens (Arnold Schwarzenegger), a sheriff of a quiet town of Sommerton, Arizona, and Gabriel Cortez (Eduardo Noriega), an escaped federal prisoner and Mexican drug kingpin. The sheriff (who has "seen enough blood and death") and a handful of townspeople stand up against the smart and ruthless criminal trying to cross the border, and a group of heavily armed mercenaries."The Last Stand" is a modern-day western, with such character actors as Luis Guzmán, Peter Stormare, Johnny Knoxville and Harry Dean Stanton (in an uncredited role) doing what they are supposed to do, and they do it very well. Arnold Schwarzenegger looks old, but he still holds his own.The film has a few shortcomings. It takes some time for the story to get moving, and Forest Whitaker's role as FBI agent doesn't fit well in the story, but once action starts, which is bloody, violent and even darkly funny, the film gets entertaining.Like "The Expendables" and its sequel, where Arnold Schwarzenegger was briefly seen, "The Last Stand" is an old-school action movie with a large amount of shootouts and physical fights. And that's pretty enjoyable.

reviewText: But he still kicks some serious A$$ with the help of his supporting characters.  They are all up against a cartel kingpin who escapes FBI custody in Vegas, who heads for the south-of-the-border in a Car-Show-Corvette.  Unfortunately, he and his advance escape team make use of the wrong town on the north side of the border and all sorts of murder, mayhem, and wisecracks ensue.  I grew up with Arnold movies in the 80s, so don't expect pre-Governator performance...but he still has the charisma and force of will to be a mature presence and focal point in a decent action movie, and this one does a good job of entertaining.  It's a shame that it flopped at the box office...the gamer and text generation doesn't appreciate a good 'lone wolf' character action flick...and my generation is too busy taking their kids to this-that-and-everything.  So, now you can at least Amazon Prime it in your living room or on your smart phone...show Arnie the love, people, because Maria sure ain't!

reviewText: This movie has an original and fairly novel plot - although I am no expert on plots. The acting is very good, and if you like Arnold the least little bit, you will want this movie. He's now an oldie but goodie and makes every scene realistic. You don't have to suspend belief, in other words. It's just a good, solid movie, and I will watch it over and over in the years to come. It qualifies as re-watchable, about like "Deja Vu" with Denzel Washington or "Red October" with Sean Connery....maybe a cut below those two, but pretty close. I'll watch it over and over mostly because I really like Arnold Schwarzenegger. If you like Forest Whitaker, as I do, this will make it even sweeter for you. He plays a non-vindictive FBI agent, and just sets off Arnold perfectly. There are some cool racecar scenes, not your typical stunt cars either. And I also like the actor playing the bad guy!
summary: Very good Schwarzenegger movie with other quality actors too

reviewText: It's great to see Arnold back at it again.  He does this kind of movie well and he certainly doesn't disappoint here.  Last Stand is not a bad movie, but falls fall short of some of Schwarzenegger's past works, such as Total Recall, Terminator 2, True Lies and Kindergarten Cop.  Perhaps the greatest short-coming of this film is that here we have a Sheriff with a thick Austrian accent working in a border town near Mexico and we are asked to believe that.  Still, The Last Stand is an entertaining, albeit very dumb film that you might find yourself enjoying the absurdity of it all.  We are, after all, talking about Arnie and he is, much to my own enjoyment, at least, back where he belongs.
summary: Not great; not bad; not one of Arnie's best

reviewText: Missing from movie screens for 9 years with a mere cameo popping up here and there, Arnold Schwarzeneger has chosen a good script for his return in Director Kim Jee-Woon's 'THE LAST STAND'-2012, a modern day western in action genre clothing.  I approached this film in slight trepidation fearing for cliches abounding and making the film more of a satire than a serious genre outing and, boy, was I thrown for a loop.  Screenwriter Andrew Knauer keeps the films running time flowing with various twists and tragedies erupting at the most unexpected moments.  The acting is first rate for this type of film:  Eduardo Noriega gives his villainous drug cartel lord the right cutting edge; Forrest Whittaker gives the perfect touch of paranoia as the FBI agent in charge; Peter Stormare pumps the villainy even more; Jaime Alexander - Rodrigo Santiago and Lus Guzman give Arnold perfect team chemistry; and there is a brief cameo by veteran Harry Dean Stanton. The highlight of the film is a fantastic car chase through a huge corn field between Arnold and Noriega brilliantly edited by Steven Kemper and photographed by Ji Yong Kim amd is worth the price of the purchase alone making it join the ranks of unique action chases.  Lionsgate releases this gorgeous Blu-Ray in a nice 2.35 1080P transfer with DTS surround sound to give it the icing on the proverbial cake.  A ton of extras including a 'making of' featurette completes the package.  Highly recommended for all action fans, this outing is truly a surprise and gives director Kim's first American film a wonderful kinetic rush introduction to his work.

reviewerName: Wilmar Luna "Author of The Silver Ninja"
reviewText: This was one of the movies that I had absolutely no interest in watching. The movie trailer did nothing for me except to show that Arnie was back in action. The problem is, I already saw him in Expendables 2, and let's be honest, he's getting a little shaky in his old age.That being said, when the movie became available for viewing on Amazon Prime, I decided to give it a shot.The acting is terrible, by far some of the worst I've seen. But all the characters had charm, even Johnny Knoxville who I'm not a big fan of. It's not that the bad acting is intentional, it's just that, you for some reason like the actors and enjoy their performance. So in a weird way, the movie just didn't really need good acting to begin with.In fact, the action scenes are freaking GREAT! There were a few times that I found myself chuckling because the reveals were just so perfectly well executed. From the big ass machine gun to the awesome shoot out in the town. This movie does not fail to deliver on the action. Also, even though I'm not a car nut, the vehicle stunts in this movie were a hell of a lot of fun to watch.You're definitely not coming into this movie for plot or acting. If you're watching this movie, it's because you want to see s*** get blown up, awesome stunts, funny moments, and Arnie kicking ass. Well if that's the case, this movie doesn't fail to deliver.Now whether you should pay money to rent the movie, well... I'm a little torn. Yes, I enjoyed myself for the most part, but at the same time, the movie left me unsatisfied. The recurring thought in my head was, "If I paid money for this. I'd be a little disappointed."If you can rent it for 1.99 or watch it for free, go with those options. It's not worth 2.99 or higher, sorry.
summary: Not an utter waste of time like other movies.

reviewText: Arnold is back. This time, he's a small-town sheriff who just wants to lead a quiet life. Then some Mexican narcotraficante in US custody escapes, in an elaborately planned and staged scheme, and is headed for Arnold's town. You can pretty much figure what happens after that.There are great chase scenes, sneering bad guys with a seemingly endless supply of expendable spear-carriers, and shoot-outs with everything up to rocket launchers. The characters are amusing, and Arnold gets a few good lines (including something like "It's people like you that give immigrants a bad name").Good commodity entertainment, but otherwise mostly forgettable.-- wiredweird

reviewText: Wow.  This was much better than expected!  Not only are the action scenes novel and thrilling, but most of them are realistic enough to enjoy.  In fact, Arnold's one major fight incorporates an homage to MMA, wrestling, and real life brawls.  Plus it has a nice twist.Most of the movie had twists that I found delightfully unexpected.  Yes, the plot is basic, but not hackneyed.  I found the movie refreshingly different, funny, and well-acted!  Arnold is stiff, but better than he's been in years.  No cheesy Expendables 2 lines.  Some meaning woven into the dialogue.Yeah, the minor characters could have been developed better.  But Knoxville is at his best, adding quite a bit of comedy relief that never takes away from the plot.  Maybe the worst part is one of the bad guys' accent.  He cannot decide if he is French or Southern.  LOL  Other than that, every actor is on point, delivering both comedic and dramatic lines really well.  I was actually surprised at Arnold's tender moments.  It was like watching a beloved statue come to life.  He's pretty stoic, but it worked.Trust me, this is no copycat Hollywood cheese-fest action flick.  Even though I am usually jaded, I cared about the characters and enjoyed the action--from car chases, to shootouts, to ambushes, to hand to hand.  This was a well-shot, novel, funny, and bloody ball!  Worth buying if you love movies like the last Rambo, Fast and Furious, or Gangster Squad.  Good stuff.
summary: Did not expect it to be this good!  Wow!
Title: The Last Stand

reviewText: This was a decent popcorn flick.  Not his best by a longshot of course but it was nice to sit back and watch a new Schwarzenegger movie once again.
